<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="EST" stage="Final" version="A">
    <Annotation class="History">
      <Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2014-12-18 07:46:26Z" when="2014-12-18 07:46:26Z" stage="Draft">Consultant Check at UBB, 6-7 Nov 2014; questions by proxy from Catherine Rountree put by Chuck; UNSs: 1. Jeferson (Son) Manupaja, male, 22, UKAW semester 7 (English); mother-father from Sabu,  speaks Sabu, has been coming to Kupang since elementary school, speaks Kupang, but too many gaps to put weight on the few words that he didn't know; 2. Yohanes Leonardo (Nardo) Ate, male, 21, UKAW semester 7 (English); mother-father from Wejewa, West Sumba, grew up in Kupang, but is a mesolectal speaker, not a basilectal speaker of Kupang; 3. Rina Fernandes, female, 22, graduated from STIBA, born in Dili, raised in Kupang, mother-Mambae, father-Tokodede, Rina was clearly the best of the three UNSs.</Message>
      <Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2014-12-19 06:29:29Z" when="2014-12-19 06:29:29Z" stage="Rev">smoothing read through for Kupang mini-Bible at UBB with Chuck, Oma Ora and Rina Fernandes.</Message>
      <Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2015-05-19 08:13:45Z" when="2015-05-19 08:13:45Z" stage="Final">Catherine Rountree approval to publish by email (reaffirmed 18 May 2015)</Message>
    </Annotation>
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">Ester</p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">Ester pung Carita<bt>The Story of Ester</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Raja Ahasuweros bekin pesta<bt>King Ahasuweros makes a party/feast</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1" />Ini carita jadi, waktu raja Ahasuweros ada pegang parenta di Persia. Dia pegang kuasa di 127 propinsi, yang tasiar dari Hindia sampe deng Sudan.<bt>This story happened/took place when king Ahasuweros was holding rule/governing in Persia. He held power/authority in 127 provinces, spread out from Hindia (India) to including Sudan. [DISCOURSE: ellipsed proposition implied by “in the days of” rendered in a passive “these events happened in the days of” (NLT), “the following events happened in the days of” (NET). But RL “these events” alone would be taken as anaphoric looking at what has been already described. “I'm going to tell you...”  or “This story happened...” is how to handle the cataphora/intro. Note: book opens and closes with implied high-level evidentials in 1:1 and 10:1-3.] [EXEG: (ftn) NLT, NET, TN, TH. Although the Greek name Xerxes is more widely known and used in NIV, NLT, CEV, NCV, etc., it is almost impossible to transliterate and/or pronounce in Indonesian and local lgs around Timor. So we go with a spelling of Ahazhueros that can be read and pronounced locally. The Indonesian transliteration is difficult for educated speakers to read [typographic /sy/ indicating a [ʃ] (mostly in Arabic loan words) which most people can't say]. HEB: hodduw: India (which was not part of the kingdom; it ran from the India border to where the Nile comes down out of the mountains in southern Sudan). See also CEV note. HEB: kuwsh: kush refers to the region immediately south and east of Egypt, including modern Nubia, the Sudan, and the Ethiopia of classical writers (not modern Abyssinia [the country now known as Ethiopia since World War 2]). It would begin at about the First cataract, where the Aswan dam now stands. ]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="almos to Etiopia"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">almos to Etiopia</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hodduw: India (which was not part"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hodduw: India (which was not part of the kingdom; it ran from the India border to where the Nile comes down out of the mountains in southern Sudan)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kuwsh: kush refers to the region"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">kuwsh: kush refers to the region immediately south and east of Egypt, including modern Nubia, the Sudan, and the Ethiopia of classical writers (not modern Abyssinia [the country now known as Ethiopia since World War 2]). It would begin at about the First cataract, where the Aswan dam now stands. A satellite, and sometimes ruler, of Egypt. ... In several cases, especially in the prophets, Ethiopia is used in parallel construction as a synonym of Egypt (Isa 20:3-5; Ezk 30:4; Nah 3:9). This probably represents the dominance of Ethiopia (or, more precisely, Nubia) over Egypt between 750 and 663 b.c. Terhakah was a notable Nubian pharaoh who tried, unsuccessfully, to block Sennacherib's westward expansion (II Kgs 19:9; Isa 37:9). After 663 b.c. Egypt was independent of Nubia (Jer 46:9; Ezk 25:4, 5, 9).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mədiynah: province. As far as the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mədiynah: province. As far as the small number of occurrences allows a test, the range of meanings is exactly the same: to govern, in the whole range of activities of government: legislative, executive, judicial or otherwise. Places with their own government.</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ini carita jadi di karaja'an Persia, yang pung pusat sakarang di negara Iran. Dalam bahasa Ibrani, ini raja pung nama, <span class="Italic">Ahazyweros,</span> yang mirip dia pung nama asli dalam bahasa Farsi (andia bahasa Persia). Ma dalam bahasa Yunani, ini raja pung nama, <span class="Italic">Xerxes.</span> Dalam tulisan sajara, na, banya orang lebe kanál dia pung nama Xerxes. Xerxes I pegang parenta dari taon 486-465 SM (SM = Sebelum Masehi). Dia pung bapa, raja Darius. Septuaginta (LXX) pake nama Artaxerxes, ma itu orang laen yang pegang parenta dari taon 464-423 SM. Bahasa Ibrani tulis <span class="Italic">hoddaw</span> (andia dari Hindia sampe deng Sudan) deng <span class="Italic">kuwsh</span> (andia Masir sampe deng Sudan, amper maso di Etiopia).<bt>This story happened/took place in the kingdom of Persia, whose center now is in the country of Iran. In the Ibrani (=Hebrew) language, this king's name is <span class="Italic">Ahazyweros,</span> which is similar to his name in the Farsi language (that is, the language of Persia). But in the Yunani (=Greek) language, this king's name is <span class="Italic">Xerxes.</span> In historical writings, na, more people know/recognise his name Xerxes. Xerxes I ruled from the years 486-465 SM (SM = Before the Messiah). His father was king Darius. The Septuagint (LXX) uses the name Artaxerxes, but that is a different person who ruled from the years 464-423 SM. The Ibrani language writes <span class="Italic">hoddaw</span> (that is from Hindia to and including Sudan), and <span class="Italic">kuwsh</span> (that is Masir [=Egypt] to and including Sudan, almost into Etiopia.</bt></note><note reference="1:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Ezra 4:6</note><v n="2" />Itu waktu, dia dudu pegang parenta dari dia pung istana di kota Susa, yang ada pung benteng kuat.<bt>At that time, he sat ruling from his palace in the city of Susa, which had a strong fort. [EXEG: Implied from the wording, there were other palaces and cities too, but for this story he happened to be ruling from Susa. See also: TN, TH. HEB biyrah = The fortified part of the city, not the whole city.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="biyrah: citadel, castle. The fortified part"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">biyrah: citadel, castle. The fortified part of the city, not the whole city.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Waktu dia su pegang parenta tiga taon, ju dia bekin pesta rame-rame kasi dia pung pagawe deng bangsawan dong samua. Dia ju undang komandan tantara Persia deng Media dong, gubernor propinsi dong, deng orang bésar laen dong samua. Dong samua datang hadir.<bt>When he had been ruling for three years, he made a festive/celebratory party/feast for all his officials and nobility.He also invited the commanders of the Persia and Media army, provincial governors, and other important people. They all attended.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishteh: drinking feast, banquet where wine"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mishteh: drinking feast, banquet where wine was served</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cheyl: force, army; the collective leadership"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">cheyl: force, army; the collective leadership of the army</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="partəmiym: noblemen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">partəmiym: noblemen</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Di itu pesta, dia kasi tunju negara pung kaya, deng dia pung hebat. Dong bagaya pake pakean mahal-mahal deng barias pake mas-perak ju. Itu pesta pung lama 180 hari.<bt>In/during that feast, he showed the wealth of the nation, and his/its amazingness/glory. They dressed up wearing various sorts of expensive clothes, and also decorated/dandied themselves using gold-silver too. The length/duration of that feast was 180 days. [STYLE: saying 180 days raises the momentous significance of the event, in contrast to saying 6 months, which diminishes it. This is backed up by local RL discourse patterns.] [EXEG: splendour &amp; finery: of the nation? of the king? A: Heb. yəqar: precious thing, splendour, honour; tipʔeret: beauty, finery (of garments, jewels), so both. This is a magnificent party where everybody is in their finery, contributing to the splendour of both.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="harʔotow (rʔh hif inf): in showing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">harʔotow (rʔh hif inf): in showing</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəqar: precious thing, splendour, honour"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yəqar: precious thing, splendour, honour</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tipʔeret: beauty, finery (of garments, jewels)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tipʔeret: beauty, finery (of garments, jewels)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01257c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Waktu itu 180 hari su abis, ju raja mau tutu samua pake pesta tuju hari yang lebe hebat lai. Samua yang tenga dalam itu benteng, kici-bésar, bapesta rame-rame di istana pung kintal.<bt>When those 180 days were finished, the king wanted to end/close it all with a 7-day feast that was even more impressive. Everyone who was in the fort, small-big (socially insignificant-important), feasted merrily/celebratory in the yard of the palace. [EXEG: Does HEB /habbira/ ‘fortress, citadel’ refer to 1) the whole city, or 2) just part of the city the palace and military complex? NRSV = vague citadel; NLT, TN, TH, TB = #2, CEV = #1; Our protocols say we go with #2. See also note at vs.2.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məloʔt: [at the] fulfillment [of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">məloʔt: [at the] fulfillment [of the days]</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nimtsəʔiym (nif partcpl): the ones who"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nimtsəʔiym (nif partcpl): the ones who were found, happened to be</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishteh: drinking party, banquet. Anything that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mishteh: drinking party, banquet. Anything that called for a celebration might be marked by a mishteh. Yearly holidays were also called a mishteh.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chətsar: enclosure, yard around something"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chətsar: enclosure, yard around something</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ginnat: garden"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ginnat: garden</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="biytan: house of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">biytan: house of</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Di itu kintal ada banya tiang dari batu marmer. Dong kasi tagantong gorden bam-banya dari kaen katun puti yang babunga warna biru. Dong ju ika itu gorden dong pake kaen lenan yang alus, deng tali warna ungu ko pasang di tiang pake cincin perak. Dong taro korsi tamu dari mas deng perak di atas lantai yang dong bekin dari ampa macam bahan: andia, ada batu mangkilat mera hati, ada marmer puti, ada kulit mutiara, deng satu batu mangkilat yang manyala macam-macam ju.<bt>In that yard there were many pillars from marble (loan: mined in nearby mountains). They hung many curtains from white cotton cloth decorated/patterned with blue. They also tied those curtains with fine/expensive linen cloth, and purple ropes to fasten to the pillars using silver rings. They placed guest chairs from gold and silver on a floor they made from four types of material: that is, there was a shiny (gem)stone that was liver red, there was white marble, there was mother of pearl, and there was a shiny (gem)stone that flashed variously too. [EXEG: NRSV, TN, TH, NLT, HCE notes.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chuwr: white stuff"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chuwr: white stuff</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karpaS: white cotton"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">karpaS: white cotton</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təkhelet: purple, the fantastically expensive purple"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">təkhelet: purple, the fantastically expensive purple dye from a gland in the Murex snail. Same idea as the Hawaiian royal capes in which every feather came from a different bird.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔachuwz (past partcpl): seized; fastened"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔachuwz (past partcpl): seized; fastened</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chavley: ropes of, cords of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chavley: ropes of, cords of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vuwts: expensive white linen from Egypt;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vuwts: expensive white linen from Egypt; a costly cloth, was a luxury import (Ezk 27:16), and therefore fit for the royal court (I Chr 15:27; cf. Est 1:6, Mordecai went to the Persian king draped with a mantle of this cloth, 8:15)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔargaman: wool dyed with red purple"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔargaman: wool dyed with red purple</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gəliyley: rings of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">gəliyley: rings of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shesh: white marble"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">shesh: white marble</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miTTowt: couches"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">miTTowt: couches</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ritsfat: mosaic pavement of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ritsfat: mosaic pavement of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bahaT: porphyry or red feldspar, or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">bahaT: porphyry or red feldspar, or possibly malachite. A dark red stone with small crystals in it, used for decoration in building. Not a jewelry stone.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dar: mother-of-pearl, like kapiz in the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">dar: mother-of-pearl, like kapiz in the Philippines, used as an inlay in other stones.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Socharet: either another kind of paving"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">Socharet: either another kind of paving stone that they used with marble, or colored bricks. Perhaps the best evidence on the meaning of so4h[eret in Est 1:6 would come from the excavation of the Persian palaces of Susa. The "pavement" if that is the precise meaning included colored stones and so4h[eret according to Esther. Excavations show much multicolored glazed bricks used in the pavement and walls of the palace of Darius (A. T. Olmstead, History of the Persian Empire, Univ. of Chicago, 1948, pp. 169-71).</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Tamu dong minum dari piala mas yang dia pung model macam-macam, deng babunga laen-laen. Ais raja pung aer anggor tapo'a-tapo'a ko kasi tunju dia pung hati bae.<bt>The guests drank from gold chalice/trophies with various shapes, and various decorations/patterns. And the king's grape juice/wine (was) poured out lavishly to show his good liver/kindness/generosity. [NOTE: see picture in TH.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hashqowt (shqh hif inf): for giving"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hashqowt (shqh hif inf): for giving people drinks</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="showniym (shnh particpl): changing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">showniym (shnh particpl): changing</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Raja kasi tau tamu dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Minum bam-banya! Jang malu-malu!&gt;&gt;<bt>The king told the guests saying, &lt;&lt;Drink a lot! Don't be shy!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju dia suru dia pung orang karjá dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Isi sampe ponu tarús. Ta'usa pake barenti.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he ordered his workers saying, &lt;&lt;Keep filling them full. There is no need to stop.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ta'usa accepted by MTTs"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">ta'usa accepted by MTTs</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shtiyyah: as for the drinking,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">shtiyyah: as for the drinking,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dat: orders"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">dat: orders</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeyn not to be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔeyn not to be</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔoneS (partcpl): compelling, compulsion"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔoneS (partcpl): compelling, compulsion</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiSSad: he founded, he appointed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yiSSad: he founded, he appointed</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rav: plenty"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">rav: plenty</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rətsown: delight, satisfaction; will, pleasure; goodwill,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">rətsown: delight, satisfaction; will, pleasure; goodwill, favour</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Waktu raja Ahasuweros ada bekin itu pesta kasi laki-laki dong, raja pung bini tua, nama Wasti, ada bekin pesta kasi parampuan dong dalam raja pung istana ju.<bt>While king Ahasuweros was making/holding that feast for the men, his senior wife, named Wasti, was also holding a feast for the women in the king's palace. [NOTE to daughter translations: bini tua indicates senior status, not old age.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Raja talalu mara deng makan gigi sang dia pung bini Wasti [\s2]<bt>The king is angry and eats teeth (furious) with his wife Wasti [EXEG: Section: NLT, TN, TH] [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Waktu hari ka-tuju, andia pesta pung hari tarahir, raja Ahasuweros talalu sanáng tagal su minum anggor bam-banya. Ju dia suru dia pung pagawe tuju orang yang layani sang dia di dia pung istana, andia: Mehuman, Bista, Harbona, Bigta, Abagta, Setar, deng Karkas,<bt>On the seventh day, that is the last day of the feast, king Ahasuweros was very happy because he had drunk a lot of wine. And he order seven of his officials who served him in his palace, that is: Mehuman, Bista, Harbona, Bigta, Abagta, Setar, and Karkas, [EXEG: note HCE discussion of why this should not be translated as ‘eunuch’ here, contra TH and TN. HCE note: “SariySiym: court-official, eunuch. The noun, meaning "(court) official," has its origin in the Akkadian title sha reshi (sharri) "the one of the (kingʔs) head." The meaning "eunuch" arose with the practice of utilizing castrated men in key positions in the various nations of the ancient near east (e.g. in Persia, Est 2:3ff.; 4:4f.) The Hebrew word is clearly related to the name of the Akkadian royal official (II Kgs 18:17). Accordingly, sa4r|&lt;s is not to be translated "eunuch" unless context or other evidence demands it.”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="SariySiym: court-official, eunuch. The noun, meaning"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">SariySiym: court-official, eunuch. The noun, meaning "(court) official," has its origin in the Akkadian title sha reshi (sharri) "the one of the (kingʔs) head." The meaning "eunuch" arose with the practice of utilizing castrated men in key positions in the various nations of the ancient near east (e.g. in Persia, Est 2:3ff.; 4:4f.) The Hebrew word is clearly related to the name of the Akkadian royal official (II Kgs 18:17). Accordingly, sa4r|&lt;s is not to be translated "eunuch" unless context or other evidence demands it.</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Tulisan bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, ini tuju pagawe dong ni, orang kabiri. Dolu-dolu ada orang kabiri yang saríng nae jadi raja pung orang parcaya yang pegang tugas macam-macam.<bt>The Ibrani language writes that these sevenmen were castrated men. Long ago there were castrated men who often rose/were appointed to be the king's trusted person who held various jobs/responsibilities.</bt></note><v n="11" />ko pi ame datang sang raja pung bini tua, Wasti. Dia suru bastél pake pakean langkáp deng topi jabatan. Te raja pung bini tua talalu cantik, andia ko raja mau kasi tunju di tamu dong.<bt>to go bring [serial verb construction] the king's senior wife, Wasti. He ordered that she dress up2 wearing the full official clothing and hat/headgear. Cuz (elaboration) the king's senior wife was very beautiful, so that is why the king wanted to show her (off) to the guests. [EXEG: HEB infinitive ‘to show’ is vague; context favours king wanting to show off queen. We take ‘crown’ as part-whole to represent full regalia (support in TN). Larger context is showing off splendour.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="keter: crown"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">keter: crown</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləharʔowt (inf): to show"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləharʔowt (inf): to show</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yafyah: her beauty"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yafyah: her beauty</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01256c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ma waktu itu pagawe dong su kasi tau raja pung parenta, ju raja pung bini manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta sonde pi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But when those officials had told the king's command, the king's wife responded saying, &lt;&lt;I'm not going.&gt;&gt; [DISCOURSE: (high-level context) /parenta/ ‘command’ here is better in this context than /pasán/ ‘message, instruction’, because of how the consequences of violating it are interpreted.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais waktu dong kambali pi lapor sang raja bagitu, ju dia pung hati panas.<bt>So when they returned and reported to the king like that, his liver was hot (=angry).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="she tell um she not going."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">she tell um she not going.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vattəmaʔer: she refused"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vattəmaʔer: she refused</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyiqtsof: he was angry, got angry"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyiqtsof: he was angry, got angry</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəmatow: his rage, his glow"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chəmatow: his rage, his glow</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baʕərah: burned"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">baʕərah: burned</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13-14" />(Naa, raja pung biasa, kalo dia mau bekin apa-apa, dia barunding dolu deng dia pung orang parcaya dong, yang tau sampe alus-alus dong pung hukum deng atoran. Yang biasa kasi nasiat sang raja, andia: Karsena, Setar, Admata, Tarsis, Meres, Marsena, deng Memukan. Dong yang jadi orang bésar di negara Persia deng Media, yang bisa maso mangada sang raja iko dong pung suka.)<bt>(Naa [+shift]. the way the king normally did things, if he wanted to do something, he would consult first with his trusted people who understood fully and in detail their laws and regulations. Those who normally advised the king were: Karsena, Setar, Admata, Tarsis, Meres, Marsena, and Memukan. These were the ones who were important people in the country of the Persia and Media, who could enter before the king whenever they liked.) [DISCOURSE: reordered for RL, to sort out background-foreground info.]</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01259c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju raja minta nasiat sang dong bilang,<bt>And the king asked their advice saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="da akamai guys"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">da akamai guys</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕittiym: the times"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕittiym: the times</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dat: orders, law"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">dat: orders, law</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="diym: law, lawsuits"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">diym: law, lawsuits</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qarov: near, friend, kindred"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">qarov: near, friend, kindred</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="riʔshonah: head, principal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">riʔshonah: head, principal</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />&lt;&lt;Waktu beta suru beta pung pagawe dong pi ame beta pung bini Wasti ko datang mangada sang beta, dia tolak deng sonde mau datang. Naa, iko kotong pung hukum deng atoran dong, beta musti kasi hukuman karmana sang dia? Te dia sonde mau iko raja pung parenta na!&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;When I ordered my officials to go bring my wife Wasti before me, she refused and didn't want to come. Naa [+shift to point], according to our-inc laws and regulations, what (kind of) punishment must I give her? Cuz (elaboration) she didn't want to follow/obey the king's command [+emphatic]!&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: king refers to himself in 3rd person to indicate this is not a family dispute, but has greater implications as king. Common in this region.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ais Memukan badiri di raja pung muka deng di muka orang bésar dong, ju manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini, bapa raja. Waktu bapa raja pung bini sonde mau dengar sang bapa raja, memang dia su hina deng bekin malu sang bapa raja. Ma bukan bapa raja sandiri sa, te dia ju hina deng bekin malu sang samua pagawe, deng samua rakyat yang ada di 127 propinsi.<bt>Then Memukan stood before the king and important people, and responded saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, father king. [DISCOURSE: Natural RL address opener.] When father king's wife didn't wans to listen/obey the king, she really showed contempt and shamed father king (=you). But not just father king alone, cuz (elaboration) she also showed contempt for and shamed all officials, and the whole populace in 127 provinces. [EXEG: HEB doesn't use the standard (theological) word for "sin," here but rather a verb meaning "act perversely". (See also CEV ‘embarrassed’ and ‘insulted’.) 127 Provinces from 1:1 repeated here to emphasize the brevity of the charge.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləvaddow: only, alone"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləvaddow: only, alone</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕawətah: she acted perversely The Hebrew"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕawətah: she acted perversely The Hebrew doesn't use the standard word for "sin," but rather a verb meaning "act perversely"</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Pasti samua parampuan di bapa raja pung da'era parenta nanti dengar dia pung bekin ni. Ais nanti dong ju sonde mau dengar-dengar sang dong pung laki, te dong bilang, &lt;Raja Ahasuweros suru dia pung bini Wasti ko datang mangada, ma dia sonde pi.&gt; Jadi dong anggap reme dong pung laki ju.<bt>Surely all women in father king's territory of rule/governing will hear of this dead of hers [NOTE: wording for ‘deed’ implies negative value.] So then they also will not want to listen to/obey their husbands, cuz (elaboration) they will say, ‘King Ahasuweros ordered his wife Wasti to come front up, but she didn't go.’ So (consequently), they will also disparage/view with contempt2 their own husbands too.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhavzowt (bzh hif): despising"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhavzowt (bzh hif): despising</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bəʕeyneyhem: in their eyes, in their"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">bəʕeyneyhem: in their eyes, in their opinions</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔamram (inf): in their saying"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔamram (inf): in their saying</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Dengar sang beta. Te ini hari ju, orang bésar dari Persia deng Media pung bini dong yang ada iko pesta di istana ni, su dengar ame dia pung bekin tu. Nanti dong ju mau iko malawan sang dong pung laki. Satu anggap reme satu. Dong bakanjar tarús, sonde pake barenti ju.<bt>Listen to me. Cuz (elaboration) this same day, the wives of important people from Persia and Media who are participating in the feast here in the palace, have already heard (svc=accomplishment) about her deed [+negative]. Later they will also want to follow in opposing their husbands. One will disparage the other. They will argue continually, without ceasing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uwkhday: and like a sufficiency of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">uwkhday: and like a sufficiency of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bizzayown: contempt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">bizzayown: contempt</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaqatsef: wrath, dissension, discord"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vaqatsef: wrath, dissension, discord</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Jadi bapa raja, beta pung usul bagini: kalo bapa raja mau, na, tulis satu surat keputusan. Cap ini surat ko biar orang tau bilang, itu kaluar dari hukum deng atoran orang Persia deng orang Media, andia ko sonde bisa roba deng sonde bisa cabu kambali. Surat pung isi musti tulis bilang, raja pung bini Wasti sonde bole datang lai di bapa raja pung muka. Biar satu kali ju, sonde bisa. Ais kasi dia pung tampa sang satu parampuan laen yang lebe bae, yang tau kasi tunju hormat sang dia pung laki, andia bapa raja sandiri.<bt>So (consequently), father king, my suggestion is like this: if father kings wants/agrees, na, write a letter of decision. (Offocial) Stamp this letter so that people know that it came out/was issued from the laws and regulations of the Persia people and the Media people, so therefore it cannot be changed, and cannot be withdrawn/revoked. The contents of the letter must write that the king's wife Wasti may not come anymore before the king. Even one time she may not. Then2, give her place to a different woman who is better, who knows how to show respect to her husband, that is, the king him/yourself. [EXEG: “my suggestion...” Basis? A: Considering vs 21 ‘my’ rather than ‘our’ fits the higher level context better. This is RL phrasing appropriate to SL discourse context of “If it pleases the king, let…” Naturalness.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yetseʔ: go forth (edict)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yetseʔ: go forth (edict)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yikkatev: let it be written"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yikkatev: let it be written</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʕəvowr: may not pass; become invalid,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yaʕəvowr: may not pass; become invalid, become obsolete (of law, decree)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lirʔuwtah: become a consort, female companion"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">lirʔuwtah: become a consort, female companion</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ais nanti kalo ini surat keputusan dari bapa raja su kuliling di 127 propinsi, na, samua parampuan, kici-besar, akan taku, ais dengar-dengar deng kasi tunju hormat sang dong pung laki.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then later when this letter of decision from the king has circulated in127 provinces, na, every woman, small-big, will be afraid, and so listen to/obey and show respect to their husband/s.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: 127 provinces from 1:1 covering “vast as it is”. ‘afraid’ implicit to explicit from context. Basis for desired response to letter. One wonders what Memucan's relationship was with his wife.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pitgam: decree"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">pitgam: decree</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rabbah: great, strong; vast"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">rabbah: great, strong; vast</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəqar: honor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yəqar: honor</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Raja Ahasuweros deng dia pung pagawe dong samua tarima bae Memukan pung nasiat tu.<bt>King Ahasuweros and his officials all accepted (favourably) Memukan's advice.</bt><v n="22" />Ais dia suru dia pung orang karjá dong ko tulis surat, iko tiap suku pung bahasa deng huruf bilang, &lt;&lt;Iko yang batúl, tiap laki musti jadi bos di dia pung ruma sandiri, deng ba'omong dalam ruma pake dia pung suku pung bahasa.&gt;&gt;<bt>So he ordered his workers to write (the) letter, according to each tribe's language and letters saying, &lt;&lt;The way things should be (lit: according to what is right), each man must be the bos in his own home, and speak in his house using the language of his people/tribe/clan.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="1:22" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dia pung maksud, kira-kira bagini: kalo orang pung bini orang asing, na, jang sampe itu bini pung bahasa yang pegang kamudi dalam ruma. Te iko raja pung mau, na, laki-laki yang musti jadi kapala dalam ruma.<bt>The intention is something like this: if a person had a foreign wife, na, may it not develop that the language of the wife holds the rudder in the home. Cuz (elaboration) according to the king's desire, na, the man is the one who must be the head in the home.</bt></note>Ju raja kirim itu surat pi 127 propinsi yang dia pegang parenta dong.<bt>And the king sent that letter to 127 provinces where he held rule/governed. [EXEG: ‘use the language of his own people’ following RSV, NET, TB, NRSV note, NLT note. The phrase is omitted from LXX. See discussion in TH and TN. NET note says, “The edict was apparently intended to reassert male prerogative with regard to two things (and not just one): sovereign and unquestioned leadership within the family unit, and the right of deciding which language was to be used in the home when a bilingual situation existed.” NIV and NLT renderings are disappointing, at best.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dong angka sang Ester jadi raja pung bini baru<bt>They elevate/install/appoint Ester to be/become the king's new wife</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1" />Lama-lama raja Ahasuweros pung mara su dingin. Ma dia inga tarús sang dia pung bini Wasti, deng dia pung bekin-bekin, ais deng surat keputusan yang kasi tau dia pung hukuman.<bt>Eventually king Ahasuweros' anger cooled. But he kept remembering his wife Wasti, and her deed [+negative], and then the letter that told of her punishment. [TEXT: LXX has ‘not’ before ‘remember’, but it is not followed by most reliable modern sources.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kəshokh (shkk inf): on abating, cooling"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">kəshokh (shkk inf): on abating, cooling</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəmat: glow, rage of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chəmat: glow, rage of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zakhar: remembered (but it doesnʔt imply"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">zakhar: remembered (but it doesnʔt imply he had forgotten about her in the meantime). More like "he gave attention to the matter, he thought it over."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nigzar (nif): it was decided about"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nigzar (nif): it was decided about her</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ais ju raja pung orang karjá yang urus sang dia, omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa raja. Botong ada mau usul bagini: biar ko botong suru orang di mana-mana ko pi cari nona-nona manis yang balóm parná tidor bakumpul deng laki-laki.<bt>So then the king's workers who served/took care of him, spoke saying, &lt;&lt;Father king. We-exc want to suggest like this: let us order people everywhere to go look for sweet/pretty young unmarried girls/women who have never slept together with a man. [EXEG: ‘everywhere’ following NLT and foreshadowing info in vs.3. Implied proposition: his attendants saw the king was distracted and wanted to do something about it.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naʕərey: boys, lads, servants of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">naʕərey: boys, lads, servants of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məshartayw (piʕel partcpl): the ones serving"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">məshartayw (piʕel partcpl): the ones serving him</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Dari tiap propinsi, bapa raja bisa angka kapala urusan ko cari nona manis dong, ais antar sang dong datang bakumpul di ini benteng di Susa. Te di sini su ada bapa Hegai, yang sonde bisa kawin,<bt>From each province, father king  (=you) can appoint supervisors to look for these pretty girls, and then escort them to gather here in the fort in Susa. Cuz (elaboration) here there is already father Hegai, who can't marry/have intercourse [+polite],</bt><note reference="2:3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Hegai tu, sonde bisa kawin, te dia orang kabiri.<bt>That Hegai can't marry/have intercourse, cuz (elaboration) he is a castrated person.</bt></note>yang bapa raja su angka ko urus parampuan di istana dong. Dia kapala urusan yang bisa jaga deng urus ini nona manis dong. Dia ju bisa ator ko biar tukang rias dong urus ini nona-nona manis pung kulit, rambut, deng pakean dong samua.<bt>whom father king has already appointed to manage/oversee the women in the palace. He is the supervisor who can guard and manage these pretty girls. He can also arrange for the beauticians to handle/manage/deal with all these pretty girls' skin, hair, and clothes. [EXEG: ‘virgin’ explicit to implicit following good RL style, since it is explicit in vs.2. Otherwise very heavy info load. This is the first time eunuchs in a harem come up, and the institution isn't familiar to our readers. There are other eunuchs for whom it's more equivalent to "courtier, official" in general, but in the case of a harem manager, sex is an issue. A king can't afford to have illegitimate sons of royal queens and concubines clouding the succession to his throne, or challenging him personally. But we pulled in a slightly different rendering from 4:5. There were special conditions for working with a king's harem. Different focus.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) This is the first time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cr) This is the first time eunuchs in a harem come up, and the institution isn't familiar to our readers. There are other eunuchs for whom it's more equivalent to "courtier" in general, but in the case of a harem manager, sex is an issue. A king can't afford to have illegitimate sons of royal queens and concubines clouding the succession to his throne, or challenging him personally. But we pulled in a slightly different rendering from 4:5, though I'd argue that "cuz" is more effective for clarifying why there were special conditions for working with a king's harem.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tukang rias: makeup, beautician,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">tukang rias: makeup, beautician,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vəyafqed (pqd hif): let him appoint"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vəyafqed (pqd hif): let him appoint</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pəqiydiym: appointees (using &quot;spesho peopo&quot; twice"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">pəqiydiym: appointees (using "spesho peopo" twice in the same verse to translate very different words is not a good idea)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vəyiqbətsuw: let them assemble. A verb"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vəyiqbətsuw: let them assemble. A verb should be used for "gather" or "assemble" that does not connote the use of force (UBS).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vətuwlah: virgin (should this be in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vətuwlah: virgin (should this be in the translation, or just carried over implicitly from Verse 2?)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="biyrah: citadel, part of a city"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">biyrah: citadel, part of a city that can be successfully defended</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="SəriyS: The noun, meaning &quot;(court) official,&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">SəriyS: The noun, meaning "(court) official," has its origin in the Akkadian title s]a re4s]i (s]arri) "the one of the (kingʔs) head." The meaning "eunuch" arose with the practice of utilizing castrated men in key positions in the various nations of the ancient near east (e.g. in Persia, Est 2:3ff.; 4:4f.) Usually is has no implications of castration, but here it does.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="natown (ntn inf): giving"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">natown (ntn inf): giving</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tamruwqeyhem (noun pl): their massages; a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tamruwqeyhem (noun pl): their massages; a scraping, rubbing (Est 2:12); their scrapings, rubbings</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ais, bapa raja bisa lia itu nona manis dong samua. Yang paling bekin sanáng bapa raja pung hati, na, bapa raja bisa angka sang dia ko jadi bini, ganti sang Wasti.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then father king can look at all the pretty girls. The one who most pleases the king's liver, na, the king can appoint her to be/become wife, replacing Wasti.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dengar itu usulan dong ju, raja tarima bae, ais bekin iko.<bt>Hearing those suggestions, the king accepted them [+favourably], and did accordingly. [NOTE to daughter translations: following RL discourse style you may need to make this direct speech. &lt;Neu&gt;??]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tiyTav (yTb imperf): is good, does"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tiyTav (yTb imperf): is good, does well, comes out best in the opinion of the king</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Itu waktu, di benteng di Susa, ada satu orang Yahudi, nama Mordekai. Dia dari suku Benyamin. Dia pung papa, Yair; dia pung ba'i Simei; deng dia pung oyang, Kis.<bt>At that time in the fort at Susa, there was a Yahudi (=Jewish) person, named Mordekai. He was of the tribe of Benyamin. His father was Yair; his grandfather was Simei; and his great-grandfather was Kis. [NOTE to daughter translations: ba'i pung papa if no term for +3 generations]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="oyang: KM great-grandfather"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">oyang: KM great-grandfather</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Dolu-dolu, waktu Nebukadnesar jadi raja di Babel, deng Yekonya jadi raja Yahuda, Nebukadnesar tangkap ame sang Yekonya, Kis, deng orang laen dong, ju paksa bawa sang dong dari Yerusalem pi Babel.<bt>Long ago, when Nabukadnesar was king in Babel, and Yekonya was king of Yahuda (=Judah), Nebukadnesar caught/captured Yekonya, Kis, and other people, and forcefully brought them from Yerusalem to Babel. [EXEG: forced travel implied by ‘prisoner’ and ‘exile’.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hoglah (glh hof): had been taken"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hoglah (glh hof): had been taken prisoner</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="golah: exiled people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">golah: exiled people</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hoglətah (hof fem sg): [people] had"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hoglətah (hof fem sg): [people] had been taken prisoner</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heglah (hif): Nebuchadnezzar took into exile,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">heglah (hif): Nebuchadnezzar took into exile, took prisoner</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Raja-raja dong 24:10-16, 2 Sajara Isra'el deng Yahuda 36:10</note><v n="7" />Andia ko ini Kis pung turunan Mordekai, bésar datang di Babel, ju dong pung kelu batamba di sana. Ais, waktu dia pung bapa kici deng dia pung bini mati, Mordekai angka bapa kici pung ana nona, ko piara sang dia sama ke dia pung ana sandiri. Itu nona pung nama pake bahasa Ibrani, andia <span class="Italic">Hadasa.</span> Deng dia pung nama pake bahasa Farsi, andia <span class="Italic">Ester.</span> Naa, Ester ni, talalu manis deng badan ba'isi.<bt>That is why the descendant of this Kis, that is Mordekai, grew up in Babel, and their family/relatives increased (in number) there. So when his uncle (FyB) and his wife died, Mordekai adapted/raised his uncle's daughter to raise her as his own child. That girl's name in the Ibrani language is <span class="Italic">Hadasa.</span> And her name in the Farsi language is <span class="Italic">Ester.</span> Naa, [+shift] this Ester was very pretty and her body was well-formed. [DISCOURSE: 1st sentence implied proposition necessary by RL discourse to set the stage.] [EXEG: TN “daughter of his paternal uncle”; but TH says could be maternal OR paternal; recommends paternal. RL cultures, more likely to take in ...?? RL lgs here also have to choose elder or younger if paternal uncle.] [NOTE to daughter translations: check your description of Rachel in Gen. 29:17; Joseph in Gen. 39:6; Moses in Acts 7:20 for good looking and well-formed.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔomen (ʔmn qal partcpl masc sg):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔomen (ʔmn qal partcpl masc sg): "In the Qal it expresses the basic concept of support and is used in the sense of the strong arms of the parent supporting the helpless infant. The constancy involved in the verbal idea is further seen in that it occurs in the Qal only as a participle (expressing continuance). The idea of support is also seen in II Kgs 18:16, where it refers to pillars of support." Here, itʔs as a foster father to Esther.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dodow: his uncle"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">dodow: his uncle</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəfat: beauty"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yəfat: beauty</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="toʔar: Thus toʔar in the OT"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">toʔar: Thus toʔar in the OT describes the form, rather than the appearance, of a beautiful woman (Gen 29:17; Deut 21:11; I Sam 25:3; Est 2:7), a handsome (RSV) man (Gen 39:6; I Kgs 1:6), sleek (RSV) or gaunt (RSV) cows (Gen 41:18f.), etc. In Gen 29:17 we rendered "but Rachel, she real good looking, wit one awesome figure" for yafat-toʔar.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bəmowt: at the time of dying"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">bəmowt: at the time of dying</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01260c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Waktu raja pung putusan so'al cere buang sang mama Wasti deng cari bini baru su tasiar pi mana-mana, dong mulai ame nona-nona manis dari samua tampa ko kumpul sang dong di benteng di Susa. Dong ju bawa ame sang Ester pi raja pung istana.<bt>When the king's decision about divorcing/getting rid of mother Wasti and looking for a new wife had spread everywhere, they began to bring various pretty girls from everywhere to gather them together at the fort in Susa. They also brought Ester to the king's palace. [EXEG: “king's order and edict” = 1) about Vashti, and 2) about gathering the virgins.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dong suru Hegai ko tanggong-jawab sang dia, te dia yang urus samua parampuan di istana.<bt>They ordered Hegai to be responsible for her, cuz (elaboration) he was the one who managed all the women in the palace.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="They did not just &quot;come&quot;; they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">They did not just "come"; they were "brought"; some officials went and brought them.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hishshamaʕ (nif inf): in being heard"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hishshamaʕ (nif inf): in being heard</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="datow: his edict (probably the one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">datow: his edict (probably the one by which he banished Vashti from the court and decided to choose another queen)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hiqqavets (nif inf): in being gathered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hiqqavets (nif inf): in being gathered</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tillaqach (nif): she was taken away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tillaqach (nif): she was taken away</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Itu kapala urusan talalu suka sang Ester, deng kasi tunju hati manis sang dia. Andia ko dia kasi Ester salap macam-macam, deng suru tukang pijit deng tukang rias ko bantu bekin dia jadi lebe cantik lai. Dia kasi Ester makanan yang bae, deng kasi dia parampuan tuju orang dari istana ko bantu sang dia. Tarús dia kasi pinda Ester dong di tampa paling bagus di parampuan istana dong pung kompleks.<bt>That supervisor really liked Ester, and showed kindness to her. That is why he gave Ester various kinds of salves, and ordered the massage people and the beauticians to help make her become even more beautiful. He gave Ester good food, and gave her seven females from the palace to help/assist her. Then2 he moved Ester (collective) to the best place in the complex/compound of the palace women.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) The Hebrew word does focus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cr) The Hebrew word does focus on massage treatments, but seems to be used here as a general word for beauticians.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Nothing more specific for &quot;beauty"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cn) Nothing more specific for "beauty treatments"? (but it is clarified in v. 12)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vattiyTav bəʕeynayw: she made an impression"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vattiyTav bəʕeynayw: she made an impression on him</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vattissaʔ: he carried"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vattissaʔ: he carried</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cheSed: kindness"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">cheSed: kindness</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayvahel (piʕel): he made haste"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayvahel (piʕel): he made haste</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tamruwqeyha: her massage, her beauty treatments"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tamruwqeyha: her massage, her beauty treatments</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="manowteha: her [very own] allotment"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">manowteha: her [very own] allotment</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rəʔuyowt (rʔh pass partcpl fem pl):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">rəʔuyowt (rʔh pass partcpl fem pl): the ones being seen, looked over; selected</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayshanneha"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayshanneha</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Naa, Mordekai su pasán memang sang Ester ko jang kasi tau sapa-sapa bilang, dia orang Yahudi, deng dia pung kelu sapa. Ju Ester bekin iko dia pung parenta.<bt>Naa [+discourse shift], Mordekai had previously instructed Ester to not tell anyone that she was a Yahudi, and who her family/relatives were. And Ester followed/obeyed his command. [EXEG: Implied proposition. anti-Semitism was rampant. TN notes “before she went to the palace” but TH says we don't know when it happened and notes the English pluperfect is used to indicate an earlier time. Kupang handles this with “memang” ‘prior, beforehand’.]</bt><v n="11" />Tiap hari Mordekai jalan bolak-balik di muka kintal dari parampuan dong pung kompleks, ko dia dapa tau Ester ada karmana.<bt>Each day Mordekai went back-and-forth in front of the yard of the women's complex/compound, so he could find out how Ester was doing. [EXEG: Heb (yaʔaseh): ‘what was being done with her’ -- implicit in ‘how Ester was doing’.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mithallekh (hitp): he walked back and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mithallekh (hitp): he walked back and forth, to and fro</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chətsar: courtyard around a building. In"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chətsar: courtyard around a building. In this case he would have been walking outside the courtyard wall.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʕaseh (nif): was being done with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yeʕaseh (nif): was being done with her</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Naa, tiap nona musti tenga 12 bulan dalam istana dolo, baru dapa dia pung urutan tidor bakumpul deng raja Ahasuweros. Dong musti iko samua atoran kasi sang parampuan di istana dong. Andia: salama 6 bulan, tukang rias dong gosok sang dong pake minya dari dara kayu wangi mur. Salama 6 bulan lai, tukang rias dong gosok sang dong pake minya wangi macam-macam deng salap yang laen dong.<bt>Naa [+shift], each girl had to stay 12 months in the palace first, before she could get her turn to sleep together with kind Ahasuweros. They had to follow/obey all the regulations for the women in the palace. That is: for six months the beauticians rubbed them with oil from the aromatic sap mur (myrrh). For another six months the beauticians rubbed them with other kinds of fragrant oils and other salves. [STYLE: note Hebrew ‘going in to’ is standard and most matter-of-fact expression for sexual intercourse. Don't go too euphemistic, but it needs to be able to be read in church.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uwvəhaggiyʕa (ngʕ hif inf): on arriving"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">uwvəhaggiyʕa (ngʕ hif inf): on arriving</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tor: turn"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tor: turn</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lavoʔ ʔel (inf): going in to,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">lavoʔ ʔel (inf): going in to, standard and most matter-of-fact expression for sexual intercourse</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qets: end; right at the end"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">qets: end; right at the end of a period of time (for beauty preparation)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dat: something obligatory"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">dat: something obligatory</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yimləʔuw: they would fulfill the time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yimləʔuw: they would fulfill the time period</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məruwqeyhem: their beauty treatments, massages"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">məruwqeyhem: their beauty treatments, massages</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mor: myrrh. In Exodus 30:23, &quot;kine"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mor: myrrh. In Exodus 30:23, "kine sap fo make perfume. Weigh da sap da way da pries guys weigh um: Myrrh perfume, sticky kine,"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bəsamiym: balsam oils"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">bəsamiym: balsam oils</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tamruwqey: beauty treatments"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tamruwqey: beauty treatments</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Kalo su sampe dia pung waktu ko satu nona maso pi tidor deng raja, na, dong kasi biar dia bole pili sandiri mau pake pakean yang mana, deng bahias pake rante mas ko perak karmana, iko dia pung suka sandiri. Dia bole minta apa sa dari parampuan dong pung kompleks di istana.<bt>When the time came for one of the girls to go in to sleep with the king, na, they allowed her to choose for herself which clothes she wanted towear, and how she wanted to decorate (accessorise?) herself with gold or silver, according to her own preferences. She could ask for whatever she liked from the complex/compound of the women in the palace.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="toʔmar: she would mention, ask for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">toʔmar: she would mention, ask for</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Kalo su mau malam, dong antar sang dia pi raja pung kamar. Dia pung beso pagi, dia sonde pulang pi kompleks pung bagian deng parampuan yang balóm tidor deng raja, ma dong musti pi di bagian deng parampuan yang su parná tidor bakumpul deng raja. Ada satu bapa lai yang sonde bisa kawin, nama Sasgas. Dia yang urus di itu bagian kadua. Kalo raja suka sang itu nona, ju minta sang dia subu pake dia pung nama, baru dia bisa kambali ko tidor ulang deng raja lai.<bt>As night was approaching, they (would) escort her to the king's room. The following morning, she didn't return to the section of the complex/compound with the women who had not yet slept with the king, but they had to go to the section with the women who had already slept together with the king. There was another man who couldn't marry/have sex, named Sasgas. He was theone who supervised/managed that second section. If the king liked a girl, and asked for her by mentioning her name, only then could she return to sleep again with the king another time. [DISCUSS; ‘bini muda’? TH says these ‘concubines’ had the status of wives, but not the same rank as the queen.] [EXEG: ‘second harem’ see note in NLT, TN, TH.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="use dea name fo tell um"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">use dea name fo tell um fo come.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sheniy: second"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">sheniy: second</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="piylagshiym: concubines; &quot;odda wife&quot; is used"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">piylagshiym: concubines; "odda wife" is used in referring to Chinese and Okinawan families where historically concubinage was a factor.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chafets: likes, is pleased with, wants"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chafets: likes, is pleased with, wants</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niqrəʔah (nif): she is summoned"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">niqrəʔah (nif): she is summoned</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15-16" />Naa, kira-kira awal bulan Januari, waktu raja Ahasuweros su pegang parenta tuju taon,<bt>Naa [+shift], around the month of January, when king Ahasuweros had held rule for seven years,</bt><note reference="2:15-16" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Tulisan bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang ini bulan ni, andia <span class="Italic">Tebeth.</span> Jadi dari orang yang pintar sajara dong, kotong bisa tau, kalo Ester maso di raja Ahasuweros antara bulan Desember pung tenga, taon 479 SM, deng bulan Januari pung tenga, taon 478 SM, iko kotong pung kalendar sakarang.<bt>Ibrani language writings say that this month was <span class="Italic">Tebeth.</span> So (consequently), according to people knowledgable about history, we can know that Ester went in to king Ahasuweros between the middle of Desember, in the year 479 SM, and the middle of Januari, in the year 478 SM, according to our calendar today.</bt></note>baru Ester dapa dia pung waktu ko maso pi istana ko tidor bakumpul deng raja. (Ester tu, andia Abihail pung ana. Abihail tu, andia Mordekai pung bapa kici. Deng Mordekai yang piara sang Ester dari kici.) Waktu Ester pung bagian ko pi istana, dia sonde minta apa-apa. Dia cuma minta nasiat dari Hegai sa, te dia yang urus parampuan yang balóm tidor deng raja. Deng dia iko itu nasiat sa. Andia ko waktu dia mau pi, samua orang yang lia sang Ester talalu suka sang dia.<bt>only then did Ester get her time to enter into the palace to sleep together with the king. (This Ester was Abihail's child. Abihail was Mordekai's uncle [FyB]. And Mordekai was the one who raised Ester from the time she was small.) When it was Ester's portion/turn to go to the palace, she did not ask for anything. She only asked advice from Hegai, cuz (elaboration) he was the one who supervised/managed the women who had not yet slept with the king. And she just followed his advice. That is why when she was about to go, everyone who saw Ester really liked her. [EXEG: timeframe, see NLT and CEV notes, TN.] [EXEG: Q: Is the admiration towards Esther 1) in general? or 2) in connection with her going to the king? A: probably both, but the immediate context favours #2, as implied by NLT, HCE and TB. CEV seems to lean toward #1. NRSV is vague. TN doesn't address this. TH notes the Heb conj links it to this context.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ester babatu (very positive)."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">Ester babatu (very positive).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="noseʔt: got"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">noseʔt: got</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chen: favorable attitude (this is general"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chen: favorable attitude (this is general background, not part of the events)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01262c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Waktu Ester pi di istana ju, raja lebe sayang sang dia dari samua parampuan yang laen dong. Dia talalu suka sang Ester deng mau tunju dia pung kasi sayang sang dia. Andia ko raja angka sang dia, deng kasi dia pake topi jabatan, ganti sang Wasti yang su kaná usir tu.<bt>When Ester went to the palace, the king loved her more that all the other women. He really liked Ester and wanted to show his love/affection to her. That is why the king elevated/appointed her, and gave her the official hat/headgear, replacing Wasti, who had been kicked out/evicted/banished. [EXEG: Heb. chesed KT here. Compare Gen 24.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyeʔəhav: loved. This is phrased as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyeʔəhav: loved. This is phrased as the next part of the story</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chen: favorable attitude"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chen: favorable attitude</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cheSed: kindness, solidarity. He figured he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">cheSed: kindness, solidarity. He figured he could have a good relationship with her.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Tarús raja bekin satu pesta bésar kasi sang Ester. Ais dia undang samua pagawe deng bangsawan ko dong makan rame-rame, deng dia kasi tamu dong hadia macam-macam yang bae. Ju dia putus bilang, itu hari jadi hari barenti karjá kasi 127 propinsi.<bt>Then2 the king made a great feast for Ester. And he invited all the officials and nobles to eat festively, and2 he gave the guests all sorts of good gifts. And he (formally) decided, that this day would be a day of rest/stopping work for 127 provinces. [EXEG: whether ‘holiday’ (NRSV, NLT, CEV, NCV) or ‘remission of taxes’ (RSV, TB) is disputed by the scholars. Most go with ‘holiday’ (significant that later NRSV diverges from earlier RSV). We restrict ‘gifts’ to the guests present at the feast for practicalities, although Heb is vague. The issue of scope of the gifts is not addressed by any sources consulted.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishteh: drinking party"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mishteh: drinking party</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hənachah: amnesty, holiday"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hənachah: amnesty, holiday</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="masʔet: portion, present, largesse, gift, contribution,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">masʔet: portion, present, largesse, gift, contribution, offering, tribute</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mordekai dapa tau ada orang yang mau bunu sang raja<bt>Mordekai finds out there are people who want to kill the king</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Waktu dong su kumpul ame nona-nona dong kali kadua,<bt>When they had gathered together the girls a second time,</bt><note reference="2:19" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Bahasa Ibrani pung maksud di sini sonde jalás.<bt>The meaning of the Ibrani language here is not clear.</bt></note>na, dong ju su angka Mordekai jadi pagawe di raja pung istana.<bt>na, they also appointed Mordekai to be an official at the king's palace. [EXEG: all sources have problems with the Heb phrase “a second time”. While the idea of the girls “transferring to the second harem” (mentioned in 2:14) certainly makes sense here, unfortunately it diverges from what the Heb text actually says. NJB and NBE also change the Hebrew text--something that generally violates our translation principles. See discussion in TN and TH. We take “sitting at the king's gate” as an official appointment, following NLT, CEV, TH, TN.]</bt><v n="20" />Ma iko Mordekai pung pasán kasi sang Ester, dia sonde parná kasi tau orang bilang, dia orang Yahudi, deng dia pung kelu sapa. Te Ester masi dengar-dengar sang Mordekai, deng bekin iko dia pung parenta samua, sama ke dolu waktu Mordekai masi piara bae-bae sang dia.<bt>But following Mordekai's instructions to Ester, she never told anyone that she was a Yahudi person, and who her family/relatives were. Cuz (elaboration) Ester still listened to/obeyed Mordekai, and did according to all his commands, just like previously when Mordekai was raising her so carefully/well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maggedet (ngd hif partcpl fem): announcing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">maggedet (ngd hif partcpl fem): announcing</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maʔəmar: word, command"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">maʔəmar: word, command</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔamnah: This noun speaks of Estherʔs"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔamnah: This noun speaks of Estherʔs having been sustained (strengthened and guided) by Mordecai as a child (Est 2:20).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01265c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Satu hari, waktu Mordekai dapa tugas di istana pung pintu maso, ada dua pagawe yang jaga di istana pung bagian dalam, yang simpan hati, ais ator siasat ko mau bunu bekin mati sang raja Ahasuweros. Dong dua tu, andia Bigtan deng Teres.<bt>One day, when Mordekai was given work/responsibility at the palace gate/entrance, there were two officials who guarded the inside section/s of the palace, who were storing liver (=stewing about something, so angry that they were intending to take action), and plotted to kill king Ahasuweros. Those two were Bigtan and Teres. [EXEG: on “sitting at the gate” see comment at vs. 19. We follow NLT and TH on interpreting “threshold” as the door to the king's private quarters within the palace. Heb: SariSey: court officials, possibly eunuchs, though in this case probably not (HCE, CEV)]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qatsaf: be angry"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">qatsaf: be angry</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="SariSey: court officials, possibly eunuchs, though"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">SariSey: court officials, possibly eunuchs, though in this case probably not</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Saf: threshold"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">Saf: threshold</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lishloach: send their hand, attack"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">lishloach: send their hand, attack</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ma Mordekai dapa tau dong dua pung rancana jahat. Ais dia kasi tau sang raja pung bini, Ester. Ju Ester pi kasi tau sang raja bilang, Mordekai yang kasi tau sang dia.<bt>But Mordekai found out about their evil plan. So he told the king's wife, Ester. And Ester went to tell the king, that Mordekai was the one who told her (about the plot).</bt><v n="23" />Waktu raja pung orang dong pareksa bae-bae itu laporan, tau-tau te itu batúl. Ais ju dong hukum itu dua orang deng tusu di atas tiang sampe mati.<bt>When the king's people had examined/interrogated that report carefully, it turned out it was correct. So the punished those two people by skewering them on a pole until dead. That matter/issue/dispute is all written down in king Ahasuweros' book of history. At that time the king also was watching them write like that. [EXEG: ‘investigate’ in Heb is a pu`al verb, subjectless. RL lgs here require that a subject be identified, and it wouldn't have been the king himself, or Esther, or Mordecai. The point is that the authorities didn't just act on Mordecai's accusation; they made their own investigation of the murder plot. Heb. word can be 1) hanged (NRSV, CEV), or 2) impaled (NLT, TB). See discussion in TH. All else being equal, we follow the TB.]</bt><note reference="2:23" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Jaman dolu dong, satu cara yang raja dong pake ko pamer dong pung kuasa sang dong pung musu yang masi idop dong, andia dong tusu musu laen dong pung mayat di tiang. Ada dua cara: 1) pake tiang tajam, ais tusu di lobang panta, tarús kasi badiri itu tiang ko biar banya orang dapa lia; 2) kasi jato mayat di atas tiang tajam ko biar itu tiang tusu di parú, ko, di pinggang. Ais kasi tenga mayat di situ ko biar samua orang dapa lia.<bt>In long ago times, one way that kings used to exhibit their power/authority to their living enemies, was to pierce/skewer the corpses of other enemies on a pole/s. There were two ways: 2) use sharp poles, then skewer the anus [acceptable term], then2 stand the pole vertical so that many people could see; 2) drop a corpse on a sharp pole so that the pole pierces/skewers the abdomen or the lower back. Then leave the corpse there so that many people could see it.</bt></note>Itu parkara samua, dong tulis abis dalam raja Ahasuweros pung buku sajara. Itu waktu, raja ju ada lia dong tulis bagitu.<Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) It's a pu`al verb, subjectless."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cr) It's a pu`al verb, subjectless. Pidgin requires that a subject be identified, and it wouldn't have been the king himself, or Esther, or Mordecai. The point is that the authorities didn't just act on Mordecai's accusation; they made their own investigation of the murder plot. But to say just "Dey aks" elicits the question "who asked?"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) I like the longer option;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cn) I like the longer option; have you exegetical support?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="babi speet = pig on a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">babi speet = pig on a spit, skewered</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayvuwqqash (puʕal): an inquiry was made"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayvuwqqash (puʕal): an inquiry was made into the matter.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyimmatseʔ (nif): it was found"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyimmatseʔ (nif): it was found</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyittaluw (nif): they were hanged, impaled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyittaluw (nif): they were hanged, impaled</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01266c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Haman mara sang Mordekai<bt>Haman is angry with Mordekai</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />Ais itu hal dong samua, ju raja Ahasuweros mau kasi tunju hormat sang Haman, andia Hamedata pung ana, yang jadi turunan dari Agag. Andia ko dia angka sang Haman lebe tinggi dari dia pung pagawe dong samua.<bt>After all that (happened), king Ahasuweros wanted to show honour to Haman, that is Hamedata's child, who was a descendant of Agag. That is why he elevated/appointed Haman higher than/above all his other officials.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="giddal (piʕel): he made him great,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">giddal (piʕel): he made him great, gave him power, promote [to prime minister]</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Samuel 15:7-33</note><v n="2" />Raja ju parenta ko kalo Haman maso-kaluar di istana pung pintu maso, na, samua pagawe yang laen dong musti tikam lutut ko kasi tunju hormat sang dia. Ais, samua kasi tunju hormat bagitu.<bt>The king also ordered that if/when Haman entered-exited the entrance of the palace, na, all the other officials must kneel to show respect to him. So then, all showed respect like that. [EXEG: Heb. korʕiym: bend, bow (of knees); hence: to bend one's knees, fall upon one's knees. Some English translations simply use ‘bow’, which can be quite trivial by comparison. Later in the story, the problem is that Mordekai does not stand up to show respect. So behind all this is the issue of showing respect.]</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01268c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ma Mordekai sonde tikam lutut deng sonde kasi tunju hormat sang Haman.<bt>But Mordekai did not kneel down and did not show respect/honour to Haman.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="korʕiym: bend, bow (of knees); hence:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">korʕiym: bend, bow (of knees); hence: to bend one's knees, fall upon one's knees</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais pagawe yang laen dong di istana pung pintu maso tanya sang Mordekai bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa! Akurang ko bapa sonde bekin iko raja pung parenta bagitu?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the other officials at the gate/entrance ofthe palace asked Mordekai saying, &lt;&lt;Father/sir! Why aren't you (father) following/obeying the king's command like that?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕowver: passing; pass over or by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕowver: passing; pass over or by or through, alienate, bring, carry, do away, take, take away, transgress; invalidate</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ju Mordekai manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni, orang Yahudi. Andia ko beta sonde bisa tikam lutut sang manusia deng barang songgo dong. Jadi beta sonde bisa tikam lutut sang Haman.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Mordekai answered/responded saying, &lt;&lt;I here am a Yahudi. That is why I can not kneel to humans and idols/gods of traditional worship. So (consequently) I cannot kneel to Haman.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: sequence from Heb tense. See CEV, TEV, TN. Implicit to explicit implications from “he was a Jew”. This carefully preserves the pattern of ‘God’ not being mentioned in the book of Esther.]</bt><note reference="3:4" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Orang pintar dong bilang, mangkali Mordekai sonde mau langgar parenta dari <span class="Italic">Kaluar dari Masir</span> 20:4-5 yang tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;Jang ukir patong yang model ke benda yang ada di langit di atas, ko, bumi di bawa, ko, dalam aer. Jang tikam lutut sang dong, deng jang sémba sang dong. Te Beta ni, bosong pung TUHAN Allah ni, camburu, deng sonde mau ko bosong kasi tunju hormat sang apa-apa yang laen, lebe dari Beta...&gt;&gt;<bt>Knowledgable people/experts say that probably Mordekai did not want to violate the command from <span class="Italic">Go Out from Egypt</span> 20:4-5 which writes saying, &lt;&lt;Do not carve statues whose form is like things in the sky above, or, the earth below, or, in the water. Do not kneel down to them, and do not worship them. Cuz (elaboration) I here, your-pl LORD God, am jealous, and do not want you-pl to show respect/honour to anything else, more than Me...&gt;&gt;</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dong buju-buju sang dia tiap hari, ma dia sonde mau dengar sang dong. Ais ju dong kasi tau sang Haman, ko mau lia kalo Haman kasi biar sang Mordekai bagitu, ko sonde.<bt>They kept cajoling/bugging him each day, but he did not want to listen to/accomodate them. So then they told Haman, to see whether Haman would allow Mordekai to do like that (= let him get away with it), or not. [EXEG: TN, TH, NLT, CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="həyaʕamduw: whether Haman would put up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">həyaʕamduw: whether Haman would put up with it; stand firm, remain, endure; to resist; to persist, persevere</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Waktu Haman dapa tau bilang, Mordekai sonde mau tikam lutut deng sonde mau kasi tunju hormat sang dia, ju Haman talalu kakodok.<bt>When Haman found out that Mordekai did not want to kneel down and did not want to show honour/respect to him, Haman was furious (lit: constricted in this throat).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyimmaleʔ chemah (nif): he was filled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyimmaleʔ chemah (nif): he was filled with rage</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ma Haman sonde puas kalo mau bunu bekin mati sang Mordekai sandiri sa. Te dia ju mau bunu bekin abis Mordekai pung bangsa Yahudi anteru di 127 propinsi yang raja Ahasuweros pegang parenta.<bt>But Haman was not satisfied to only kill Mordekai alone. Cuz (elaboration) he also wanted to kill off Mordekai's entire Yahudi race in the 127 provinces in which king Ahasuweros held rule/governed. [EXEG: on “disdained” “beneath him” see NLT, CEV. On “lay hands on” = kill, see discussion in TH, CEV.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyivez (bzh): he despised"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyivez (bzh): he despised</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhashmiyd (shmd hif): destroy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhashmiyd (shmd hif): destroy</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Haman ator siasat ko mau bunu samua orang Yahudi<bt>Haman plots to kill all the Yahudi people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Dalam bulan April, waktu raja Ahasuweros su pegang parenta 12 taon, Haman suru bilang, &lt;&lt;Cari tau kasi beta, waktu yang pas ko kotong bunu bekin abis Mordekai pung bangsa Yahudi dong.&gt;&gt; Ais dong hela lot di Haman pung muka, ko cari tau bagitu. Ju itu lot jato kaná di tanggal 7 Maret, taon muka.<bt>During the month of April, when king Ahasuweros had been holding rule for 12 years, Haman ordered saying, &lt;&lt;Find out for me the best time for us-inc to kill off Mordekai's Yahudi race/people.&gt;&gt; So they drew lots in frontof Haman, to find that out. And the lot fell to/on the 7th of Maret, the following year. [EXEG: on time, see NLT text &amp; note, HCE, plus vaguer discussion in TH, TN.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Is this what you did"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cn) Is this what you did for casting lots in the N.T.?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:7" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, dong hela lot di bulan <span class="Italic">Nisan,</span> andia bulan Maret-April iko kotong pung kalender. Itu lot kasi tunju bulan <span class="Italic">Adar</span>, andia bulan Pebruari-Maret. Lia ju <span class="Italic">Ester</span> 3:13. Ini samua jadi kira-kira taon 472 SM (Sebelum Masehi). Alkitab bahasa Kupang ni salin itu tanggal dong iko kotong pung kalender sakarang. Kalo &lt;lot&gt;, bahasa Ibrani bilang, <span class="Italic">pur</span> (bentuk tunggal). Andia sampe sakarang, tiap taon orang Yahudi bekin pesta <span class="Italic">Purim (pur-im:</span> bentuk jamak) ko inga ini carita yang Tuhan pake Ester deng Mordekai ko kasi salamat sang dong.<bt>The Ibrani language Bible writes that they drew lots in the month of <span class="Italic">Nisan,</span> that is the months of Maret-April according to our-inc calendar. That lot pointed to the month of <span class="Italic">Adar</span>, that is Pebruari-Maret. See also <span class="Italic">Ester</span> 3:13. This all happened around the year 472 SM (Before Messiah). The Kupang language Bible here transfers those dates to follow our current calendar (system). As for &lt;lot&gt;, the Ibrani language says, <span class="Italic">pur</span> (singular form). That is why now, each year the Yahudi people make the feast of <span class="Italic">Purim(pur-im:</span> plural form) to remember this story of how God used Ester and Mordekai to *save them.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ju Haman pi di raja Ahasuweros ko kokoe bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa raja yang mulia! Ada satu bangsa asing yang idop tasiar di bapa pung 127 propinsi samua. Ma dong idop tapisa dari samua. Dong ju sombong deng sonde mau bacampor deng bangsa laen dong di sini. Dong pung adat deng atoran beda dari samua suku-bangsa laen, dong ju sonde bekin iko bapa raja pung atoran dong. Sonde pantas kalo dong sonde mau hormat kotong pung atoran bagitu. Jadi ada lebe bae, bapa raja sonde usa kasi biar ko dong idop lai.<bt>Then Haman went to king Ahasuweros ko pursuade him saying, &lt;&lt;Most glorious father king! [+literary Malay, still used today in addressing high officials] There is a strange/foreign race who lives scattered throughout all of father's (=your) 127 provinces. But they live separately from everyone else. They are also arrogant and don't want to mix/integrate with other races here. Their customs/traditions/traditional law and regulations are different from all other races. It is not right/appropriate that they do not want to show proper respect for our regulations like that. It would be better/best, if father king would not allow/permit them to live anymore. [EXEG: 2 diff Heb word lean towards hukum adat for the first, including ‘customs’, and toward hukum/peraturan for the second, more like ‘laws &amp; regs. Heb also uses 2 vbs indicating ‘spread throughout’ but ‘separated, isolated, keeping to themselves’. Also HCE.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeshnow (yesh): it exists?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yeshnow (yesh): it exists?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məfuzzar (pzr puʕal partcpl pass): scattered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">məfuzzar (pzr puʕal partcpl pass): scattered</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məforad (prd puʕal partcpl pass): spread"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">məforad (prd puʕal partcpl pass): spread out, separated [?]; (1) to the separation of a river into tributaries (Gen 2:10); (2) the separation of the wings of a bird (Ezk 1:11; cf. Job 41:17 [H 9]); (3) the separation of friends on an amiable basis (Gen 13:9, 11, 14; Ruth 1:17; II Sam 1:23; (4) the dispersal of peoples (Gen 10:5, 32; 25:23; Deut 32:8).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vədateyhem: their laws; Haman charged the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vədateyhem: their laws; Haman charged the Jews with practicing different laws-laws allegedly incompatible with those of the Persians (3:8). "Laws" in this sense comes close to the meaning of "customs" and "religious practices." (from Persian)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shonowt (shnh partcpl fem pl): changed,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">shonowt (shnh partcpl fem pl): changed, changing; different</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="datey: laws of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">datey: laws of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="showet (shwh partcpl fem): being like"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">showet (shwh partcpl fem): being like (not clear)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləchanniycham (nwch hif inf): laying down,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləchanniycham (nwch hif inf): laying down, depositing (not clear)</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Kalo iko bapa raja pung mau, beta usul bagini: bapa raja susun satu surat parenta yang tulis bilang, samua rakyat yang laen dong musti kasi ancor abis ini bangsa yang tar laku-laku dong. Kalo bapa raja satuju, na, biar ko beta kasi sang bendahara yang urus bapa raja pung doi, 10.000 karong doi perak.<bt>If it pleases the king (lit: if it accords with father king's desires), this is what I would suggest: father king compose a letter of command/law which writes saying, all the other citizens/populace must completely destroy this worthless/useless race. If father king agrees, na, permit me to give the treasurer who manages the king's money, 10,000 (gunny/rice) sacks of silver money.</bt><note reference="3:9" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;10.000 <span class="Italic">talenta&gt;&gt;.</span> Satu talenta pung barát, andia 34 kilogram. Andia Haman tawar ko kasi 340 ton doi perak! Ada orang yang pintar dong pikir bilang, jang sampe Haman mau dapa kambali itu doi samua, deng rampas ame harta dari orang Yahudi yang dia bunu dong.<bt>The Ibrani language Bible writes saying, &lt;&lt;10,000 <span class="Italic">talenta&gt;&gt;.</span> The weight of one talenta was 34 kilograpms. In that way Haman offered to give 340 tons of silver money! There are clever/knowledgable people/experts who think that perhaps Haman wanted to get all his money back, by robbing the possessions of the Yahudi people that he killed.</bt></note>Ais pake itu doi dong ko bayar orang yang urus itu parkara dong.<bt>Then use that money to pay people who handle that matter/issue/dispute. [EXEG: value of 10,000 talents, see NLT, TN, TH.  “the men who carry out the business” See NCV, HCE, TN, TH]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yikkatev (nif): let it be written"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yikkatev (nif): let it be written</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləʔabdam (piʕel): to destroy them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləʔabdam (piʕel): to destroy them</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeshqowl: I will weigh out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔeshqowl: I will weigh out</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhaviyʔ (bwʔ hif inf): to bring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhaviyʔ (bwʔ hif inf): to bring</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ginzey: treasury of (from Persian)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ginzey: treasury of (from Persian)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01270c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Bapa raja bilang, &lt;&lt;Neu.&gt;&gt; Ais dia kasi kaluar dia pung cincin stempel dari dia pung jari, ju sarakan kasi sang Haman ko cap bekin sah itu surat parenta. (Haman tu, yang bamusu deng bangsa Yahudi dong. Dia tu, andia Hamedata pung ana, yang jadi turunan dari Agag.)<bt>The king said, &lt;&lt;Neu. [OK, acquiesce]&gt;&gt; Then he took off his signet ring from his hand, and turned it over to Haman to stamp making legal/official that letter of law/command. (That Haman is the one who was enemies with/at enmity with the Yahudi race. He was Hamedata's child, who was a descendant of Agag.) [EXEG: implied proposition, see NLT]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyaSar (Swr hif): he took off"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyaSar (Swr hif): he took off</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Tabbaʕtow: seal-ring, signet-ring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">Tabbaʕtow: seal-ring, signet-ring</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ju raja kasi tau sang Haman bilang, &lt;&lt;Itu doi dong, tarsará sang lu sa. Deng lu mau bekin apa sang itu bangsa tu, itu ju tarsará sang lu sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the king told Haman saying, &lt;&lt;That money thing, is up to you. And whatever you want to do with that race, that is also up to you.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: (ambiguity): Heb. “the money is given to you” = 1) you don't need to pay the treasury 10,000 talents as you promised, OR 2) the wealth of the Jews' is given to you as booty. Most translations try to preserve the ambiguity. TEV, CEV goes to #2. See discussion in TH. DISCOURSE: paragraph break for separate event from 10. The parenthetical background stuff in 10 makes the break.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) One interpretation of 7:4 is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cr) One interpretation of 7:4 is that Esther knows by then that the king is not going to get the money from Haman if the Jews aren't wiped out. She makes the pitch that keeping her and her people alive is worth more than Haman is going to give, and she's fighting for her life. The loss of the money, nevertheless, may help explain why the king gets so furious in 7:5. We've changed "keep da money" here to the more ambiguous "No worry bout da money," taken from the parallel situation in Genesis, because it keeps open the possibility that Haman is going to pay. And in 7:4 we ended up with the other legitimate exegetical position, namely that slavery would have been a minor inconvenience in comparison to causing trouble for the king, so the issue of Haman's silver is kept out of it. Better that minor inconvenience than to cause trouble for the reader by having to describe the unspoken moves in Near Eastern bargaining customs.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) See query on 7:4"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cn) See query on 7:4</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="natuwn (ntn partcpl pass): is given"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">natuwn (ntn partcpl pass): is given [to you] = keep it. But see the note in 7:4; this "keep da money" may be culturally like when Abraham is dickering for his burial cave, and heʔs told "Iʔll give it to you," but as both parties expect, he ends up paying more than itʔs really worth.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Jadi tanggal 17 April, Haman kumpul ame raja pung juru tulis dong. Dong susun satu surat parenta iko parsís ke Haman suru sang dong. Dong tulis kasi tiap gubernor di tiap propinsi. Dong ju tulis kasi tiap bangsa deng suku pung tua-tua adat. Dong tulis iko tiap propinsi deng bangsa pung bahasa deng huruf dong. Tiap surat yang mau kaluar pake raja Ahasuweros pung nama, deng tanda cap dari raja pung cincin stempel sandiri yang dia su sarakan kasi sang Haman tu.<bt>So (consequently), on 17 April, Haman gathered together the king's scribes. They composed a letter of command/law following exactly what Haman order them (to write). They wrote to each governor in each province. They also wrote to each race and tribe's traditional elders. They wrote according to each province and race and language with their (own) letters. Each letter that was about to go out used king Ahasuweros' name, and stamp from his own signet ring that he had turned over to Haman. [EXEG: time following NLT. Haman summoning secretaries following CEV.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəchashdarpəney: satraps of; the Persian empire"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔəchashdarpəney: satraps of; the Persian empire was divided into 20 satrapies, or major administrative areas stretching from Afghanistan to Sudan. Each satrapy had a bunch of districts in it.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pachowt: governors of provinces, local governors"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">pachowt: governors of provinces, local governors</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khtavah: its writing system"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">khtavah: its writing system</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shem: in the name of, with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">shem: in the name of, with the authority of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nechtam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nechtam</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ais dong kasi itu surat dong samua sang tukang bawa pasán dong ko mau lari bawa kasi itu surat pi itu 127 propinsi dong. Itu surat dong samua pung isi parenta yang sama bilang, &lt;&lt;Pamimpin dong musti ator ko biar nanti tanggal 7 Maret, dong musti bunu bekin mati deng kasi ancor abis samua orang Yahudi, laki-laki-parampuan, kici-bésar, tua-muda samua. Orang yang urus itu parkara ju bole rampas ame orang Yahudi pung harta milik dong samua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they gave all those letter to the messengers so they could run and deliver those letters to the 127 provinces. The letters all contained the same command saying, &lt;&lt;Leaders must arrange things so that on 7 Maret, they must kill and completely destroy/annihilate all Yahudi people, male-female, small-big, old-young all of them [LEX: Local RL categories.] The people handling this issue/matter/dispute may also take/snatch/rob all the possessions/belonging of the Yahudi people.&gt;&gt; [DISCOURSE: catetories in natural RL order. The runners don't actually go until vs.15, so this is irrealis here.] [EXEG: time following NLT. Heb (ambiguity): is the loot for those who organise? or for those who carry out? We follow NLT. Implied: because vs.12 is focusing on different place, people, languages, and writing systems, in vs. 13 we make it explicit that all these letters said the same thing.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ratsiym (rwts partcpl pl): runners"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ratsiym (rwts partcpl pl): runners</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhashmiyd (shmd hif inf): to destroy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhashmiyd (shmd hif inf): to destroy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləʔabbed (piʕel): destroy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləʔabbed (piʕel): destroy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Taf: children"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">Taf: children</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəlalam: their spoil, prey, booty; gain"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">shəlalam: their spoil, prey, booty; gain</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lavowz (bzz): take as spoil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">lavowz (bzz): take as spoil</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Kalo itu surat dong su sampe di da'era, dong musti tulis ulang dia pung isi, ko biar rakyat di tiap propinsi deng bangsa bisa tau dia pung isi, ju siap-siap ko mau bunu bekin mati abis samua orang Yahudi pas dia pung hari.<bt>If/when those letters had arrived in the regions, they were to rewrite the contents, so that the citizens/populace in each province and race could know its contents, and be prepared to kill off all the Yahudi people on the exact day. [EXEG: as in Heb. vs. 14 copies written; vs. 15 copies sent out.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patshegen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">patshegen</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhinnaten (nif): to be given [as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhinnaten (nif): to be given [as law]</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="galuwy (glh partcpl pass sing): uncovered,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">galuwy (glh partcpl pass sing): uncovered, made clear</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕətidiym: ready (pl)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕətidiym: ready (pl)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01271c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Waktu raja parenta tukang bawa pasán dong ko pi bawa capát, ju dong langsung lari bawa kasi itu surat parenta pi samua tampa. Di kota Susa ju, dong tempel itu surat ko biar samua rakyat bisa tau. Ais ju raja dudu makan-minum deng Haman. Ma rakyat di kota Susa dong ada tabingung-bingung.<bt>When the king ordered the messengers to take them quickly, they straight away ran carrying those letters of command/law to all places. Also in the city of Susa, they posted that letter so that all the citizens/populace could know (its contents). After that, the king sat and ate-drank with Haman. But the citizens of the city of Susa were confused. [EXEG: BART note: ‘drink’ here is metonymy for a full meal. Also TH.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) SK Mo betta &quot;on top"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cr) SK Mo betta "on top da strong wall". Jalike da paypa dey put on top da telephone pole so you know wea fo go fo da party. "On top" doesn't mean English "on top"; it means "on," like "go on top dat bus" means "get on that bus," not "climb up on top of that bus."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Did you test the meaning"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cn) Did you test the meaning of "inside da strong wall"? How would someone read that? (if it's inside the wall)?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dəchufiym (dchp partcpl pass): done in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">dəchufiym (dchp partcpl pass): done in haste</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="navowkhah (bwk nif): was in confusion;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">navowkhah (bwk nif): was in confusion; wandered in confusion</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mordekai minta ko Ester tolong sang dia pung orang Yahudi sandiri<bt>Mordekai asks Ester to help her own Yahudi people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />Waktu Mordekai dapa tau samua hal yang Haman dong mau bekin sang orang Yahudi dong, ju dia robek dia pung pakean dari badan. Ais dia ganti pake sarong dari karong goni, ju po'a abu di dia pung kapala sandiri ko jadi tanda bilang, dia pung hati talalu susa. Tarús dia kaluar dari dia pung ruma bagitu, pi kota pung jalan dong, ju manangis kuat-kuat dari dia pung hati yang pait.<bt>When Mordekai found out everything that Haman (coll) wanted to do to the Yahudi people, he tore his clothes from/on his body. Then he changed to wear a wrap from gunny sack/cloth, and poured dust on his own head as a sign that his liver was troubled/distressed. Then2 he went out from his house like that, going to the streets of the city and crying loudly form his bitter liver. [EXEG-1: The Heb dual action “tear/shredded his clothes” and “put on sackcloth and ashes” is assumed in our part of the world to replace the torn clothes with the sackcloth, and it seems one reading of the Heb certainly allows that. Otherwise, one is putting sackcloth over the torn clothes, and I've never heard anybody suggest that, nor read it in the commentaries. My [CEG] understanding of “wearing sackcloth” includes putting up with suffering the discomfort of the prickly cloth directly against the skin, in concert with the distress/grief that triggered it. Because of that assumption, the local worldview naturally adds “from the body”, which people do when they are in a rage or extreme distress.] [EXEG-2: Heb. marah: bitter; similar figurative uses around Timor.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyiqraʕ: he tore"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyiqraʕ: he tore</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyizʕaq: he cried out for help"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyizʕaq: he cried out for help</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="marah: bitter"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">marah: bitter</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ma waktu sampe di istana pung pintu maso, dia sonde jadi maso, tagal orang yang pake sarong dari karong goni sonde bole maso di situ.<bt>But when he arrived at the entrance/gate of the palace, he was not able to enter, because people who wore wraps from gunny sack/cloth were not allowed to enter there. [EXEG: Heb word in vs. 1 /vayyizʕaq/ can also imply ‘cry out for help’, implying in vs.2 he went to the palace seeking help.]</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01273c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Waktu raja pung surat parenta sampe di tiap propinsi, ais dia pung rakyat dengar itu surat pung isi, ju orang Yahudi dong samua hati susa. Dong manangis kuat-kuat, sama ke ada orang baru mati. Ju dong puasa. Dong banya baganti pake sarong dari karong goni, ju dong po'a abu di dong pung kapala sandiri ko jadi tanda bilang, dong pung hati susa.<bt>When the king's letter of command/law arrived in each province, and the citizens/populace heard the contents of that letter, the Yahudi people's livers were all troubled/distressed. They cried loudly, just like someone had just died. And they fasted. Many of them changed to wear wraps from gunny sacks/cloth, and they poured ashes on their own heads as a sing that their livers were troubled/distressed. [EXEG: Heb. miʃped: mourning with loud shrieks. Every week the TV news shows mourners in Near Eastern countries acting the same way.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="datow: his edict"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">datow: his edict</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maggiaʕ (ngʕ hif partcpl): arrived"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">maggiaʕ (ngʕ hif partcpl): arrived</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔevel: mourning for the dead"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔevel: mourning for the dead</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsowm: fasting"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tsowm: fasting</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vəkhiy: weeping"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vəkhiy: weeping</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miSped: mourning with loud shrieks. Every"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">miSped: mourning with loud shrieks. Every week the TV news shows mourners in Near Eastern countries acting the same way.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yuttsaʕ (ntsʕ hof): was spread"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yuttsaʕ (ntsʕ hof): was spread</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Waktu parampuan yang bantu Ester dong, deng laki-laki yang jaga parampuan dong datang kasi tau Ester so'al Mordekai, ju Ester pung hati susa mau mati. Ais dia kirim kasi Mordekai pakean yang bae, ko ganti itu karong goni. Ma dia sonde mau tarima.<bt>When the women who assisted Ester, and the men who guarded the women came and told Ester about Mordekai, Ester's liver was extremely distressed/troubled. So she sent Mordekai good clothes to replace the gunny sack. But he didn't want to accept them (=he rejected them). [DISCOURSE (referent tracking): Heb. uses ‘queen’ here. We undertranslate it (like CEV) as not in focus; in local RLs would be heavy information load here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="wtbwʔynh: they came to her"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">wtbwʔynh: they came to her</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vattitchalchal (chwl hitpalpel): she was distressed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vattitchalchal (chwl hitpalpel): she was distressed</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhalbiysh (lbsh hif inf): to clothe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhalbiysh (lbsh hif inf): to clothe him [with]</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhaSiyr (Swr hif inf): to put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhaSiyr (Swr hif inf): to put away, get rid of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qibbel (piʕel): take, accept"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">qibbel (piʕel): take, accept</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ais Ester pange datang satu orang, nama Hatak. (Dia tu, satu laki-laki yang sonde bisa kawin, yang raja suru karjá kasi sang Ester.) Ju Ester suru Hatak ko pi cari sang Mordekai, ko cari tau akurang ko Mordekai hati susa ko pake karong goni deng manangis kuat-kuat bagitu.<bt>Then Ester summoned a person named Hatak. (He was a man who could not marry/have sex, whom the king had ordered to work for Ester.) And Ester ordered Hatak to go look for Mordekai, to find out why Mordekai's liver was troubled/distressed (enough) to wear gunny sack and cry loudly in that way.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vattətsawwehuw: she ordered him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vattətsawwehuw: she ordered him</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01274c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Andia ko Hatak kaluar pi cari Mordekai di tana lapang di muka istana pung pintu maso, ju tanya sang dia iko Ester pung pasán.<bt>That is why Hatak went out and looked for Mordekai on the open field/square in front of the entrance/gate of the palace, and asked him following/according to Ester's instructions. [DISCOURSE: ellipted proposition: and asked him...]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ais Mordekai kasi tau samua-samua. Dia ju carita kasi tau barapa banya doi yang Haman su tawar mau kasi maso di raja pung bendahara, ko biar orang dong bunu kasi abis samua orang Yahudi.<bt>So Mordekai explained everything. He also told how much money Haman had offered to put into the king's treasurer, so that people would kill off all the Yahudi people. [EXEG: “happened to him” understranslated as per NLT, CEV.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qarahuw: all that had befallen him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">qarahuw: all that had befallen him</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parashat: exact statement"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">parashat: exact statement</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="byhwdyym: to the Jews"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">byhwdyym: to the Jews</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləʔabbədam (piʕel inf): to destroy them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləʔabbədam (piʕel inf): to destroy them</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ju Mordekai kasi sang Hatak satu surat parenta yang dong su tempel di kota Susa, yang tulis bilang, raja suru ko bunu kasi abis samua orang Yahudi di 127 propinsi. Ais Mordekai minta sang Hatak bilang, &lt;&lt;Pi kasi tunju ini surat sang raja pung bini, Ester. Carita samua-samua sang dia. Ais bilang beta yang suru sang dia ko pi mangada sang raja ko bela dia pung bangsa sandiri, deng minta ko biar raja kasi tunju dia pung hati bae sang botong samua.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Mordekai gave Hatak one of the letters they had posted in the city of Susa, which wrote saying, the king ordered to kill off all the Yahudi people in 127 provinces. Then Mordekai requested Hatak saying, &lt;&lt;Go show this letter to the king's wife, Ester. Tell here everything. And say I am the one who order her to go front up before the king to defend her own race, and request the king to show his good liver/goodness/kindness/generosity to all of us-exc.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: on “charging, ordering, directing” Ester, see TH discussion that Mordekai is exerting his social right as “father, uncle”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patshegen: copy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">patshegen: copy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kətav-haddat: written form of the edict"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">kətav-haddat: written form of the edict</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhashmiydam (shmd hif inf): the killing,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhashmiydam (shmd hif inf): the killing, desctruction</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləharʔowt (rʔh hif inf): to show"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləharʔowt (rʔh hif inf): to show</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lətsawwot (tswh piʕel inf): to order,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">lətsawwot (tswh piʕel inf): to order, appoint</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhitchannen (chnn hitp inf): pray for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhitchannen (chnn hitp inf): pray for mercy, seek favor, implore mercy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləvaqqesh (piʕel inf): seek, require"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləvaqqesh (piʕel inf): seek, require</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ju Hatak pulang ko carita sang Ester samua-samua yang Mordekai bilang.<bt>So Hatak returned to tell Ester everything that Mordekai had said.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01277c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ais Ester suru Hatak bawa pasán kambali pi sang Mordekai bilang,<bt>Then Ester ordered Hatak to take instructions/message back to Mordekai saying,</bt><v n="11" />&lt;&lt;Bagini: ada satu atoran yang samua orang karjá di istana deng samua rakyat di 127 propinsi dong su tau. Andia, kalo ada laki-laki ko parampuan yang pi deka-deka deng raja di dia pung kamar parenta, padahal raja sonde parná pange sang dong, na, dia pung atoran bilang, itu orang musti kaná hukum mati. Cuma ada satu jalan kaluar sa, andia kalo raja sorong dia pung tongkat parenta mas. Kalo raja bekin bagitu, baru itu orang bisa salamat. Ma inga te, su 30 hari ni raja sonde pange beta datang.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;It's like this: there is a regulation that all workers in the palace and all the citizens/populate in 127 provinces already know. That is, if there is a man or a woman who approaches the king in his ruling/governing room, but in fact the king has never summoned him/her, na, the regulation says that person must be punished by death. There is only one way out, that is if the king stretches out his gold rulingstaff/scepter. If the king does that, only then can that person be saved/rescued. But remember/keep in mind, cuz (elaboration) it has already been 30 days since the king summoned me to come/the king has not summoned me to come for 30 days now.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chatser: courtyard around a building"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chatser: courtyard around a building</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pəniymiyt: inner"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">pəniymiyt: inner</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yiqqareʔ (nif): is [not] called, summoned"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yiqqareʔ (nif): is [not] called, summoned</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləvad: only, except"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləvad: only, except</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yowshiyT (hif): he holds out something"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yowshiyT (hif): he holds out something to somebody</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sharviyT: scepter"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">sharviyT: scepter</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niqreʔtiy (nif): I have [not] been"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">niqreʔtiy (nif): I have [not] been called, summoned</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ais Hatak pi kasi tau Mordekai samua yang Ester su bilang.<bt>Then Hatak went and told Mordekai everything that Ester had said. [EXEG: Hatak, instead of “they”, following LXX, NLT, HCE.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ju Mordekai manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Pi kasi tau sang raja pung bini, Ester bilang, &lt;Jang pikir bilang, lu sandiri sa orang Yahudi yang sonde kaná bunu, tagal lu tenga dalam raja pung istana.<bt>So Mordekai responded saying, &lt;&lt;Go tell the king's wife, Ester saying, &lt;Don't think that, you alone of the Yahudi people will not be killed, because you live in the king's palace.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tədammiy (dmh piʕel): [donʔt] you liken,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tədammiy (dmh piʕel): [donʔt] you liken, devise</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhimmaleT (nif): escaping (whatʔs the relationship"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhimmaleT (nif): escaping (whatʔs the relationship between beyt-hammelekh and this?)</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Ma inga te, kalo lu sonde omong apa-apa sakarang, nanti jalan kaluar deng jalan salamat kasi orang Yahudi dong muncul datang dari orang laen. Ma kalo jadi bagitu, lu deng lu pung kelu dong samua ancor buang. Sapa tau? Jang sampe lu jadi raja pung bini sakarang, ko cuma urus ini satu parkara sa.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>But remember/keep in mind, cuz (elaboration) if you do not say anything now, later a way out and a way of salvation/rescue for the Yahudi people will appear from another/different person. But if that happens, you and your family will all be completely destroyed. Who knows? (RQ) Perhaps you have become the king's wife now, only to handle/deal with this one issue/matter/dispute.&gt;&gt;&gt; [EXEG: The book of Esther is famous for never mentioning the name of God. It would be easier to render this verse using ‘God’ as Actor, but we've done it this way to preserve the style.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəresh (hif inf abs): refrain from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chəresh (hif inf abs): refrain from speaking &gt; reacting &gt; acting</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tichəriyshiy (hif inf abs): you refrain"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tichəriyshiy (hif inf abs): you refrain from speaking &gt; reacting &gt; acting</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rewach: relief, space, respite"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">rewach: relief, space, respite</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hattsalah: deliverance"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hattsalah: deliverance</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʕəmowd: will stand up, arise; to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yaʕəmowd: will stand up, arise; to be constituted, set, appointed; since Esther is famous for not mentioning God, we had probably better not mention him in the translation if we can work around it.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="toʔviduw: you will [all] perish"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">toʔviduw: you will [all] perish</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uwmiy yowdeaʕ: who is in a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">uwmiy yowdeaʕ: who is in a position to know? who knows?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kazoʔt: like this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">kazoʔt: like this</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="higgaʕat (ngʕ hif): you have arrived"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">higgaʕat (ngʕ hif): you have arrived</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malkhuwt: royal power, reign, kingdom"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">malkhuwt: royal power, reign, kingdom</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ais Ester kirim pasán kasi sang Mordekai bilang,<bt>Then Ester sent a message to Mordekai saying,</bt><v n="16" />&lt;&lt;Pi kumpul ame samua orang Yahudi di kota Susa ni. Beta minta ko bosong puasa deng sambayang kasi sang beta tiga siang, tiga malam. Jang makan, deng jang minum sadiki ju. Beta deng beta pung parampuan karjá dong ju puasa deng sambayang bagitu. Ais itu, biar beta langgar atoran, ma beta mau maso mangada sang raja. Kalo beta musti mati, na, biar beta mati.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;Go gather together all the Yahudi people here in the city of Susa. I request that you-pl fast and pray for me three days and three nights. Do not eat and do not drink even a little. I and my female workers will also fast and pray like that. After that, even if/though I violate/transgress the regulation, nevertheless I will go in to front up before the king. If I must die, na, let me die (= so be it).&gt;&gt; [EXEG: fast = fast &amp; pray, implied by symbolic action; TH, TN, HCE.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kənowS (imperv): gather"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">kənowS (imperv): gather</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nimtsəʔiym (mtsʔ nif partcpl pl): the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nimtsəʔiym (mtsʔ nif partcpl pl): the ones who are found</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsuwmuw (imperv pl): fast"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tsuwmuw (imperv pl): fast</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ju Mordekai pulang, ais bekin iko Ester pung pasán samua.<bt>Then Mordekai returned home, and then did according to Ester's entire message/instructions.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyaʕəvor: he passed, went away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyaʕəvor: he passed, went away</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsiwwətah (tswh piʕel): she ordered, instructed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tsiwwətah (tswh piʕel): she ordered, instructed</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ester undang raja ko datang makan pesta<bt>Ester invites the king to come eat (at) a feast</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="5" />
      <v n="1" />Waktu dong su puasa tiga hari, Ester pake dia pung pakean jabatan yang alus, ju pi badiri pas di muka raja pung pintu. Itu pintu tu, yang maso pi raja pung tampa parenta. Raja ada dudu di atas dia pung korsi parenta yang bamangada deng itu pintu. Itu pintu tu, tabuka lebar.<bt>When they had fasted (for) three days, Ester put on her fine/expensive/elegant official clothes, and went and stood right in front of the king's door. That door was the one that entered into the king's place of ruling/governing. The king was sitting on his ruling chair which mutually faced that door. That door was wide open.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vattilbash (qal): she put on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vattilbash (qal): she put on</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vattaʕəmod: she took her stand"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vattaʕəmod: she took her stand</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2015-11-15 01:49:37Z">o</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pəniymiyt: inner"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">pəniymiyt: inner</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nokhach: in front, straight in front"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nokhach: in front, straight in front</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="petach: opening, entrance, doorway"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">petach: opening, entrance, doorway</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Waktu raja lia Ester ada badiri di muka pintu, ju dia pung hati sanáng. Andia ko dia sorong dia pung tongkat parenta dari mas yang ada di dia pung tangan ko kasi tunju bilang, dia mau tarima bae sang Ester. Ais Ester maju pi muka, ju sonto itu tongkat pung ujung.<bt>When the king saw Ester was standing in front of the door, his liver was happy/gladdened. That is why he extended/stretched out his gold ruling staff/scepter in his hand to indicate that he wanted to accept/receive Ester well/positively. Then Ester advanced forward, and touched the end of that scepter.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rəʔowt (rʔh inf): wen he saw"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">rəʔowt (rʔh inf): wen he saw</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nasʔah: she experienced, received a favorable"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nasʔah: she experienced, received a favorable attitude in his eyes</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyowsheT (ysht hif): he held out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyowsheT (ysht hif): he held out</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sharbiyT: scepter. A staff or *rod,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">sharbiyT: scepter. A staff or *rod, often very ornate, borne as a symbol of personal sovereignty or authority, normally by kings, but the same word is used of the rod of office of others (Gn. 38:18; Lv. 27:32; Ps. 23:4; Mi. 7:14; Is. 28:27). The term HarebX (Akkad. HaBiTTu) is used only of the sceptre of Persian rulers (Est. 4:11; 5:2; 8:4).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vattiggaʕ"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vattiggaʕ</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01279c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ju raja tanya sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Karmana, Ester? Ada parlú apa? Mau minta apa di beta, na, kasi tau sa! Nanti beta kasi. Biar mau minta bagi dua beta pung harta karaja'an ju, beta kasi.&gt;&gt;<bt>So the king asked her saying, &lt;&lt;How is it, Ester? What do you need? Whatever you want to request of me, na, just tell me! I will give/grant it. Even if you request half of the wealth of the kingdom, I will give it.&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: Compare wording in Mark 6:22-23.] [EXEG: TH notes lg is formal here, and Heb uses ‘queen’ term in address. JEG notes there is disagreement among commentators whether ‘half the kingdom’ refers to territory, or wealth and resources within the kingdom, the latter making more sense in the original social &amp; political context. Most English translations go literal here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malkhuwt: my kingdom (Itʔs not &quot;I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">malkhuwt: my kingdom (Itʔs not "I goin give you plenny ... cuz I da king", but "da stuffs dat stay mines cuz I da king" or even "da rights I get cuz I da king".)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vəyinnaten (ntn hif): shall be given"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vəyinnaten (ntn hif): shall be given to you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ais Ester manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa raja yang mulia. Beta ada siap meja ko bekin satu pesta kasi sang bapa raja. Jadi, kalo bapa raja suka, na, nanti bapa datang ko makan pesta. Kalo mau, na, tolong bawa Haman datang ju. Te sadiki lai samua su siap na!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Ester responded saying, &lt;&lt;Most glorious Father king. [STYLE: mirroring classical literary Malay, but Kupang variety.] I am preparing a table to make a feast for father king  (=you). So (consequently), if it pleases father king, na, father should come to eat that feast. If you want, na, please bring Haman along too. Cuz (elaboration) in a little bit/soon everything will already be ready! [+emphatic]&gt;&gt; [EXEG: in Heb “and Haman” is presented as an afterthought. Timing: Heb can be ‘daylight’, ‘today’, ‘during this calendar day’. There should be a sense of urgency, since Heb says ‘I have made’, so TEV ‘tonight’ is a bit weak. Strategically in the plot it appears Esther doesn't want to give Haman (or the king) time to ponder “what's behind this?”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) In Hebrew it's presented as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cr) In Hebrew it's presented as an afterthought; "come the king and Haman" has a masculine singular verb. Same thing for Verse 8. On the other hand, the singular may just be courtly idiom in which only the king is addressed even when other people are part of the conversation.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) nice; so natural, with the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cn) nice; so natural, with the "afterthought"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishteh: in Ezr 3:7 refers to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mishteh: in Ezr 3:7 refers to that which is drunk, such as wine. Elsewhere it means a "banquet" or a "feast." It is used of a special meal prepared for honored guests, as in Gen 19:3, in which Abraham hosts the angels (cf. also Gen 26:30 and II Sam 3:20). It is used also of wedding feasts such as Jacobʔs in Gen 29:22 and the seven day wedding feast of Samson in Jud 14:10-17. Anything that called for a celebration might be marked by a mishteh.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Tarús raja suru dia pung orang dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Pi cari Haman ko suru dia datang sakarang. Capát! Te botong mau iko mama raja pung minta.&gt;&gt; Ju dong pi.<bt>Then3 the king ordered his people saying, &lt;&lt;Go find Haman, so order him to come now. Quickly! Cuz (elaboration) we-ecs want to follow mother king's request.&gt;&gt; So they went. [STYLE: In RLs here it is appropriate to refer to Ester as “mother king” since that would be her role to all present in the room, other than the king. It is typical in this region to address someone ascribing the role from the perspective of junior rank present.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mahəruw (piʕel imperv pl): make Haman"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mahəruw (piʕel imperv pl): make Haman hasten, hurry up and bring, bring Haman right away to do what Ester says.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Waktu Haman su datang, ju dia iko sama-sama deng raja ko pi makan pesta yang Ester ada siap kasi sang dong.<bt>When Haman had come, he accompanied the king to go eat the feast which Ester was preparing for them. [DISCOURSE: implied propositions filled in 5a and 5b for RL discourse.]</bt><v n="6" />Waktu dong ada minum anggor, ju raja tanya ulang sang Ester bilang, &lt;&lt;Karmana, Ester? Sakarang su bisa kasi tau, lu ada parlú apa? Lu mau minta apa sang beta, na, kasi tau sa! Nanti beta kasi. Biar lu minta bagi dua beta pung harta karaja'an ju, beta kasi.&gt;&gt;<bt>While they were drinking wine, the king again asked Ester saying, &lt;&lt;How about it, Ester? Now you can tell me, what is it that you need? Whatever you want to request from me, na, just tell me! I will give/grant it. Even if you request half of the belongings/wealth of my kingdom, I will give it.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sshəʔelatkha: your request"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">sshəʔelatkha: your request</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vəteʕas (nif): it shall be done"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vəteʕas (nif): it shall be done</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ais Ester kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa raja yang beta sayang. Beta pung parlú bagini sa:<bt>So then Ester told him saying, &lt;&lt;My beloved king. This is what my need/request is:</bt><v n="8" />kalo bapa raja sayang sang beta, deng mau bekin iko beta pung minta, na, beta usul bagini: biar beso beta bekin satu pesta lai kasi sang bapa raja. Beso, kalo datang makan pesta di sini, baru beta kasi tau beta pung parlú. Haman bisa iko datang ju.&gt;&gt;<bt>if father king loves me, and wants to do according to my request, na, may I suggest like this: tomorrow let me make another feast for father king. Tomorrow, if/wehn you come east the feast here, only then will I tell/explain my need/request. Haman can also come.&gt;&gt; [STYLE: preserving the style of Haman seeming to be an afterthought.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="matsaʔtiy chen: if I have found"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">matsaʔtiy chen: if I have found favor. The vast majority of occurrences are secular and not theological in significance. In contrast with the verb chanan, the focus of attention is not on the giver, but on the recipient, of what is given. In contrast with the frequent occurrences of the verb and other derivatives, in the Psalms chen occurs but twice in Ps 84:11 [H 12] "the Lord will give favor" (RSV), and in Ps 45:2 [H 3] of the "grace" on the lips of the bridegroom. h[e4n appears thirteen times in Proverbs, often with an aesthetic significance of charm or beauty. As Neubauer has stressed, many of the passages in which this phrase is found concern the relations of a superior to an inferior, e.g. a king to his subject.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Haman saki hati, ko mau bunu sang Mordekai<bt>Haman is vengeful, wanting to kill Mordekai</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Itu hari, waktu Haman mau pulang dari itu pesta, ju dia pung hati babunga deng sanáng. Ma waktu dia kaluar dari istana pung pintu maso, dia lia Mordekai sonde badiri ko kasi tunju hormat sang dia, deng sonde kasi tunju rasa taku sadiki ju. Itu bekin Haman tamba jengkel lai sang Mordekai.<bt>That day, when Haman was about to go home from that feast, his liver was flowered (idiom: overjoyed) and happy. But when he went out from the gate/entrance to the palace, he saw Mordekai not standing to show respect tohim and also not showing even a little fear. That made Haman increasingly upset with Mordekai.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sameach (adj): joyful"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">sameach (adj): joyful</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Towv lev: delighted; &quot;good [glad, merry"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">Towv lev: delighted; "good [glad, merry of heart]" that TEV interprets as being "in a good mood."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zaʕ (zwʕ): he [did not] tremble;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">zaʕ (zwʕ): he [did not] tremble; showed no fear, did not tremble nervously</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyimmaleʔ (piʕel): he was filled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyimmaleʔ (piʕel): he was filled</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chemah: rage"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chemah: rage</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Biar dia makan gigi bagitu ju, dia tahan diri, ko pulang ruma.<bt>Even though he ate teeth like that (idiom: furious), he restrained himself to go/and went home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyitʔappaq (ʔpq hitp): he restrained himself"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyitʔappaq (ʔpq hitp): he restrained himself</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01280c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Sampe deng sampe ju, dia pange datang dia pung tamán dong, deng dia pung bini Seres.<bt>Upon arriving (idiomatic grammatical construction for simultaneous action), he summoned his friends and his wife, Seres.</bt><v n="11" />Waktu dong su bakumpul, ju Haman omong bésar bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta pung harta ada banya. Beta pung anak-anak ada banya ju. Ais raja ada kasi tunju hormat sang beta deng cara macam-macam. Dia ju angka sang beta lebe tinggi dari samua pagawe deng orang bésar laen dong yang karjá kasi sang dia.<bt>When they had gathered together, Haman bragged (idiom: spoke big) saying, &lt;&lt;I have much wealth. And I also have many children. And, the king is showing honour/respect to me in various ways. He has also elevated/appointed me higher than all other officials and important people who work for him. [DISCOURSE: Made direct speech following preferred RL pattern.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vaySapper (piʕel): he recounted, go over"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vaySapper (piʕel): he recounted, go over a story, go through a list of accomplishments</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕashrow: his wealth"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕashrow: his wealth</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nissəʔow: [the king] had exalted him,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nissəʔow: [the king] had exalted him, advanced him to a higher position</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Bukan raja sandiri sa yang kasi tunju hormat sang beta, ma tadi raja pung bini Ester ju minta ko raja deng beta pi makan pesta yang dia su ator. Cuma botong dua sa! Sonde ada orang laen lai! Bukan itu sa, ma dia ju su undang ko beso raja deng beta pi makan pesta lai di situ. Hebat, aa?<bt>Not only the king himself is the one who is showing honour/respect to me, but earlier the king's wife Ester also asked the king and I to go eat a feast that she arranged It was just the two of us! There was nobody else! Not only that, but also she has invited to that tomorrow the king and I go eat another feast there. Amazing/impressive, huh? [KM: aa = confirmative tag]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔaf: even more"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔaf: even more</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heviyʔah (bwʔ hif): she brought"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">heviyʔah (bwʔ hif): she brought</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qaruwʔ (passive partcpl): invited"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">qaruwʔ (passive partcpl): invited</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ma beta rasa ke itu samua sonde ada pung arti apa-apa. Te tiap kali beta maso-kaluar lewat istana pung pintu maso tu, beta lia itu orang Yahudi, andia Mordekai, ada dudu di situ. Dia sonde parná badiri ko kasi tunju hormat sang beta! Su talalu lebe ni!&gt;&gt;<bt>But I feel as if all that has not meaning whatsoever. Cuz (elaboration) each time I enter-exit via the gate/entrance of the palace, I see that Yahudi person, that is Mordekai, is sitting there. He has never stood to show respect to me! That's too much!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="showeh (partcpl): Est 7:4 (perhaps the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">showeh (partcpl): Est 7:4 (perhaps the hardest verse in this book to translate), "For would not this affliction (liquidation of the Jews) ʔamount to/be comparable toʔ a loss to the king?" or "for our affliction is not ʔto be comparedʔ to the king?" Two verses, Isa 40:25; 46:5, use sha4wa= to express Godʔs incomparability. With him no one can be compared. The verb occurs also in Est 3:8, 5:13 and Job 33:27 where the idea of comparison is latent but not expressible in English translation.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ais Haman pung bini, Seres, deng dia pung tamán dong samua, omong bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo bagitu, na, botong usul bagini: suru orang ko kasi badiri satu tiang gantong yang tinggi 22 meter.<bt>Then Haman's wife Seres, and all his friends, spoke saying, &lt;&lt;If it is like that, na, we-exc suggest like this: order people to erect a hanging pole that is 22 meters high.</bt><note reference="5:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, itu tiang gantong pung tinggi &lt;&lt;50 <span class="Italic">'amma&gt;&gt;.</span> Andia, 50 hasta, ko kira-kira 22,5 meter.<bt>The Ibrani language Bible writes saying, that hanging pole's height was &lt;&lt;50 <span class="Italic">'amma&gt;&gt;.</span> That is 50 hasta [Indonesian word for ‘cubit’], or approximately 22.5 meters.</bt></note>Tarús beso pagi minta raja ko suru orang gantong ame sang Mordekai di situ sampe mati. Ais nanti, kalo iko makan pesta sama-sama deng raja, lu pung hati bisa tanáng, te lu pung parkara deng Mordekai su abis.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then3 tomorrow morning ask the kingto order people to hang Mordekai there until dead. So then later if/wehn you participate in eating the feast together with the king, your liver can be calm/settled, cuz (elaboration) your issue/matter/dispute with Mordekai is over/settled/done.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: different views on whether the Heb word refers to sharp pole to be impaled upon [NLT, TB], or a gallows to hang him form. Most go with the latter.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju Haman tarima bae dong pung usul, ais dia suru orang ko kasi badiri itu tiang gantong, ko biar dia bisa gantong kasi mati Mordekai di situ.<bt>And Haman accepted (positively) their suggestion, so then he ordered people to erect that hanging pole, so that he could hang Mordekai to death there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕets: tree, pole (we would call"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕets: tree, pole (we would call it a gallows)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gavoah: high"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">gavoah: high</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vəyitluw (tlh pl): let them [the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vəyitluw (tlh pl): let them [the kingʔs men]</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sameach"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">sameach</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Raja kasi tunju hormat sang Mordekai<bt>The king honours/shows respect to Mordekai</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="6" />
      <v n="1" />Itu malam ju, raja susa tidor. Ais lama-lama dia suru orang bilang, &lt;&lt;Bawa datang itu tulisan yang carita samua-samua yang su jadi, mulai dari dong angka sang beta jadi raja!&gt;&gt; Ju orang pi ame itu tulisan dong, ais baca ko biar raja bisa dengar.<bt>That same night, the king had trouble sleeping. Then eventually he ordered people saying, &lt;&lt;Bring that/those writings here which tell everything that has happened, beginning from when they first elevated/installed me as king!&gt;&gt; So people went and fetched those writings, then read them so the king could hear/listen. [DISCOURSE: made direct quote following RL style. Also irealis-realis following good RL style.] [EXEG: Q: Everything or just memorable events? A: Two issues. 1) RL grammar. It's either everything (= all that is considered important by the compilers, but see below), vs. only one or two specific events. This is the natural way of phrasing it in these lgs without overtranslation/skewing the focus. 2) the genre of annals/chronicles in that region in that era: I've looked at some of the ancient Sumerian and related texts. They go into some pretty incredible detail at times, and highlight things that we might not consider important or relevant (you see a bit of this in the Illiad and Odyssey too). So at the one extreme “everything (without exception)” is impossible and unlikely, and at the other, TN &amp; TH “(important/memorable) events” I think is a bit of reading our worldview into it (how we would do it) without actually looking at what kinds of stuff was included in this genre.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nadədah (fem): it fled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nadədah (fem): it fled</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shənat: sleep of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">shənat: sleep of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zikhronowt: memory, remembrance; memorial; celebration (of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">zikhronowt: memory, remembrance; memorial; celebration (of a day); memorial sentence; memorial sign. The "book of records" (Est 6:1; KJV) was a written reminder of Mordecaiʔs deeds. Not like the Guinness Book of World Records, which "record book" could also refer to.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dibrey hayyamiym: the affairs of each"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">dibrey hayyamiym: the affairs of each day</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niqraʔiym (nif partcpl pl): be read,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">niqraʔiym (nif partcpl pl): be read, have read</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Baca-baca, ju dong baca parkara dolu, waktu Mordekai dapa tau bilang, raja pung dua pagawe yang jaga di istana, andia Bigtan deng Teres, su ator siasat ko mau bunu sang raja Ahasuweros. Ju Mordekai kasi tau orang ko dong jang bunu ame sang raja. Ais ju orang su tulis itu parkara dalam itu tulisan, te itu dong pung sajara.<bt>They kept reading along, and they read that matter/incident previously, when Mordekai had found out that two of the king's officials who guarded the palace, that is Bigtan and Teres, had plotted wanting to kill king Ahasuweros. And Mordekai had told people so they wouldn't kill (accomplishment scv) the king. After that, people had written that matter/incident in the writings, cuz (elaboration) that was their history.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyimmatseʔ (nif): they found written"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyimmatseʔ (nif): they found written</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Saf: threshold"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">Saf: threshold</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lishloach yad: put out their hand"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">lishloach yad: put out their hand = kill</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Ester 2:21-22</note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01281c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Dengar itu carita, ju raja tanya dia pung orang karjá dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Kotong su bekin apa, ko kasi tunju hormat sang Mordekai? Te dia su kasi salamat sang beta, na!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that story, the king asked his workers saying, &lt;&lt;What did we do to show honour/respect to Mordekai? Cuz (elaboration) he saved me [+emphatic]!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəqar: splendour, honour"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yəqar: splendour, honour</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uwgəduwllah: greatness"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">uwgəduwllah: greatness</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məshartayw: as his servants"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">məshartayw: as his servants</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa raja jang mara, ma kotong sonde parná bekin apa-apa kasi sang dia.&gt;&gt;<bt>They answered/responded saying, &lt;&lt;Father king don't be angry [NOTE: can also mean ‘apologies’ in KM], but we have never done anything for him.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Naa, itu waktu Haman baru maso di luar raja pung ruang parenta, ko mau minta raja gantong bekin mati sang Mordekai di itu tiang gantong yang dia baru kasi badiri tu.<bt>Naa [+shift], at that time Haman had just entered right outside the king's ruling/governing room, to ask the king to hang to death Mordekai on that hanging pole which he had just erected.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="litlowt: to hang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">litlowt: to hang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hekhiyn (kwn hif): cause to be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hekhiyn (kwn hif): cause to be placed, set up</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju raja lia ada orang yang badiri di ruang tunggu, ais dia tanya bilang, &lt;&lt;Sapa yang ada di situ tu?&gt;&gt;<bt>And the king saw there was someone standing in the waiting room, so he asked saying, &lt;&lt;Who is that out there?&gt;&gt; [EXEG: Q: support for king saw someone out there? A: Fair question. I think people are so used to messed up chronology in the Hebrew, perhaps they are missing some obvious clues from the Hebrew grammar here that indicate things are out of sequence. But many capture it in one way or another. Heb. a) king said/asked ‘who is out there?’ b) for (elaboration) Haman had (just) come into the outer court. I.e. he saw or heard something that triggered the king's question; it was not a question out of the blue. Cf. SPCL &amp; CEV resequencing; TN calls it “a brief flashback”; NRSV: “The king said, ‘Who is in the court?’ Now Haman had just entered the outer court…”, NLT: “‘Who is that in the outer court?’ the king inquired. As it happened, Haman had just arrived in the outer court…”, CEV: “About this time, Haman came in to ask the king to have Mordecai hanged on the tower he had built. The king saw him and asked, ‘Who is that man waiting in front of the throne room?’” TB “Siapakah itu yang ada di pelataran?” (who is that [specific/definite] who is out there in the courtyard? … At that time Haman had just come/arrived…). In Kupang this broad word for “saw” can also be used for “perceived/sensed” without the eyes having to have seen something concrete.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ju raja pung orang karjá dong manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Itu, andia Haman yang ada badiri di ruang tunggu.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the king's workers responded saying, &lt;&lt;That is Haman who is standing in the waiting room.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais raja parenta bilang, &lt;&lt;Suru dia maso sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>So the king commanded saying, &lt;&lt;Order him to come in!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hinneh: behold, reference to current situation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hinneh: behold, reference to current situation</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yavowʔ: may he come inside, let"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yavowʔ: may he come inside, let him come in</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01283c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ju Haman maso datang. Ais raja langsung tanya sang dia bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo raja mau kasi tunju hormat sang satu orang, na, raja musti bekin karmana?&gt;&gt;<bt>So Haman came in. Then the king immediately asked him saying, &lt;&lt;If/when the king wants to show honour/respect to a certain person, na, what/how should the king do?&gt;&gt; [STYLE: common for important people to refer to themselves by their 3s title like this.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Naa, Haman ada pikir bilang, &lt;&lt;Pasti raja mau kasi tunju hormat sang beta ni. Te sonde mungkin ada orang laen lai yang lebe hebat dari beta na!&gt;&gt;<bt>Naa [+shift to background explanation], Haman was thinking that, &lt;&lt;Surely the king wants to show honour/respect to me here. Cuz (elaboration) it is not likely/probable that there is another person who is greater/more impressive than me [+emphatic]!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chafets: like, be pleased with, want"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chafets: like, be pleased with, want</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="biyqrow: splendour, honour"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">biyqrow: splendour, honour</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yowter: more, better"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yowter: more, better</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Jadi dia kasi tau sang raja bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa raja! Beta pung usul bagini: kalo bapa raja mau kasi tunju hormat sang satu orang, na,<bt>So (consequently) he told the king saying, &lt;&lt;Father king! My suggestion is like this: if/when father king wants to show honour/respect to a certain person, na,</bt><v n="8" />suru orang karjá dong ko bawa bapa raja pung baju satu yang bapa raja parná pake. Deng bawa bapa raja pung kuda satu yang ada pake bapa raja pung tanda jabatan di dia pung kapala.<bt>order the workers to bring one of father king's shirt/clothes that father king has worn. And bring one of father king's horses which wears father king's sign of position/status/rank on his head. [NOTE: This is not putting a crown on a horse, but putting an insignia that shows that this is the king's horse.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="keter: crown. This is not putting"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">keter: crown. This is not putting a crown on a horse, but putting an insignia that shows that this is the king's horse.</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ais sarakan itu baju deng itu kuda sang bapa raja pung pagawe tinggi satu, ko biar dia yang kasi pake itu baju sang itu orang yang bapa raja mau kasi tunju hormat sang dia. Deng itu pagawe ju yang musti kasi nae itu orang di bapa raja pung kuda. Ais ju suru itu pagawe ko antar bawa itu orang di kota pung tana lapang deng jalan bésar dong. Itu pagawe ju musti jalan di muka itu kuda, deng batarea kasi tau bilang, &lt;Kalo raja mau kasi tunju hormat sang satu orang, na, dia kasi tunju deng cara bagini su!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Then (have them) hand over that clothes and that horse to one of the king's highest officials so that he puts (causes to wear) that clothes on that person whom father king wishes to show respect to him. And that official should cause to mount that person on father king's horse. After that, order that official to escort that person on the city's open fieldsquare and its main roads. And that official must walk in front of the horse and shout out explaining that, &lt;If/when the king wants to show honour/respect to a certain person, na, he shows it in this way/manner!&gt;&gt;&gt; [EXEG: Heb. ‘city square’ includes main streets. Compare TH, NRSV, NLT, NIV, CEV. We envision this including both, as either/or seems unlikely.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔiysh: someone who - the whole"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔiysh: someone who - the whole thing is general: this is the sort of thing the king is glad to do for anyone he wants to honor.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="missarey: one of the nobles"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">missarey: one of the nobles</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="partəmiym: the nobility"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">partəmiym: the nobility</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hilbiyshuw: and they will dress the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hilbiyshuw: and they will dress the man</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hirkiyvuhuw (hif): they will cause him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hirkiyvuhuw (hif): they will cause him to ride</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kakhah: thus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">kakhah: thus</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yeʕaseh (nif): to be done"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yeʕaseh (nif): to be done</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Dengar bagitu, ju raja suru sang Haman bilang, &lt;&lt;Neu! Sakarang lu pi ko pili ame itu baju deng kuda, parsís ke lu pung omong tadi tu. Ada satu orang Yahudi, nama Mordekai, yang biasa dapa tugas di istana pung pintu maso. Lari capát-capát ko bekin iko lu pung omong tadi samua kasi sang dia. Jang kurang satu apa ju! Te beta mau kasi tunju hormat sang dia na!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that, then the king ordered Haman saying, &lt;&lt;OK, fine! Now you go select/choose that clothes and horse, exactly as you said just now. There is a Yahudi person, named Mordekai, whose normal work/responsibility is at the entrance/gate to the palace. Run quickly and do to/for him according to everything that you said just now. Don't leave anything out/don't be lacking in anything! Cuz (elaboration) I really must/need to honour him [+emphatic]!&gt;&gt; [STYLE (naturalness): Last sentence implicit to explicit to reinforce purpose and speaker attitude. Natural RL discourse.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maher (piʕel imperv): hurry!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">maher (piʕel imperv): hurry!</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔal-tappel (npl hif): do not cause"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔal-tappel (npl hif): do not cause to fall; do not fail to do anything</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01285c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Jadi mau tar mau Haman pi ame itu baju deng itu kuda. Ju dia kasi pake itu baju di Mordekai, ais kasi nae sang dia di itu kuda. Ju Haman antar dia kuliling di kota pung jalan bésar dong, deng batarea bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo raja mau kasi tunju hormat sang satu orang, na, dia kasi tunju deng cara bagini su!&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) whether he wanted to or not (idiomatic), Haman went and got/fetched that clothes and that horse. And he put those clothes on Mordekai, and then mounted him on that horse. Then Haman escorted him around the main streets of the city, and shouted out saying, &lt;&lt;If/when the king wants to show honour/respect to a certain person, na, he shows it in this way/manner!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kakhah: thus does he do"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">kakhah: thus does he do</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Antar abis, ju Mordekai kambali tugas di istana pung pintu maso.<bt>When he had finished escorting, then Mordekai returned to his work/responsibility at the entrance/gate of the palace.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ma Haman rasa malu mati. Andia ko dia pulang capát-capát deng tutu muka pake kaen.<bt>But Haman was embarrassed/ashamed. That is why he went home quickly and covered his face with a cloth. [EXEG: mourning-shame; see TN, TH, NLT, CEV. (TWOT brings out sense of ‘intense emotion’.)]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nidchaf (nif): he hurried"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nidchaf (nif): he hurried</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔavel: mourning"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔavel: mourning</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəfuwy (chph partcpl pass): covered up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chəfuwy (chph partcpl pass): covered up</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Pulang deng pulang ju, dia carita kasi tau samua-samua sang dia pung bini Seres, deng dia pung tamán yang dia parcaya dong.<bt>Upon arriving home (idiomatic construction indicating simultaneous action), he told explaining everything to his wife Seres, and his friends that he trusted.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ju dong kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Aduu! Itu Mordekai tu, orang Yahudi. Lu su kala. Pasti lu su mulai jato ni, ma. Sonde mungkin lu bisa malawan ame sang dia!&gt;&gt;<bt>And they told (him) saying, &lt;&lt;Aduu [+regret]! That Mordekai is a Yahudi person. You've already lost. Surely you have begun to fall (socially/morally/stature), [+contrary to expectation]. It's not likely/probably that you can successfully oppose him!&gt;&gt; [EXEG: See TH for treating ‘if’ as ‘since’. See TH also for Jews defeating Amalekites.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qarahuw: they have met, befallen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">qarahuw: they have met, befallen</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəkhamayw: his wise men, advisers, brain"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chəkhamayw: his wise men, advisers, brain trust</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zeraʕ: seed, offspring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">zeraʕ: seed, offspring</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hachillowta (chll hif): you have begun"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hachillowta (chll hif): you have begun</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="linpol (inf): to fall, to fail"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">linpol (inf): to fall, to fail</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nafowl tippowl (inf abs): you will"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nafowl tippowl (inf abs): you will fail utterly</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:13" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Mangkali Haman pung tamán dong su tau <span class="Italic">Tuhan pung Tulisan Barisi</span> yang tulis bilang orang Yahudi harus kasi kala orang Amalek. Lia <span class="Italic">Kaluar dari Masir</span> 17:8-16; <span class="Italic">Daftar Sensus</span> 24:20; <span class="Italic">Carita Ulang so'al Jalan Idop</span> 25:17-19; <span class="Italic">1 Samuel</span> 15:7-33.<bt>Perhaps Haman's friends knew <span class="Italic">God's Clean/Holy Writings</span> which wrote that the Yahudi people had to defeat the Amalek people. See <span class="Italic">Going Out from Egypt</span> 17:8-16; <span class="Italic">Census List</span> 24:20; <span class="Italic">Retelling about Life's Way</span> 25:17-19; <span class="Italic">1 Samuel</span> 15:7-33.</bt></note><v n="14" />Waktu dong masi ba'omong, ju raja pung pagawe dong datang ame sang Haman, ais antar dia capát-capát ko pi makan pesta yang Ester su siap.<bt>While they were still speaking, the king's officials came and got Haman, and took/escorted him quickly to eat the feast which Ester had prepared.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="higgiyʕuw (ngʕ hif): they arrived"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">higgiyʕuw (ngʕ hif): they arrived</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyavhiluw (bhl hif): they hurried"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyavhiluw (bhl hif): they hurried</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sanjata makan tuan<bt>A weapon eats its master/owner [Kupang idiom] [ALT: Ester pancing ame sang Haman, air raja hukum mati sang Haman]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="7" />
      <v n="1" />Ais raja deng Haman datang makan pesta sama-sama deng mama raja Ester.<bt>Then the king and Haman came and ate the feast together with mother king Ester [NOTE to daughter translations: In some lgs this can be ambiguous as 1) queen, 2) king's wife, 3) king's mother. We want #2 here, so don't force it to be literal.]</bt><v n="2" />Itu pesta kadua, waktu dong ada minum aer anggor, ju raja tanya ulang sang Ester bilang, &lt;&lt;Mama raja ada parlú apa? Lu mau minta apa sang beta, na, kasi tau sa! Te nanti beta kasi. Biar mau minta bagi dua beta pung harta karaja'an ju, beta kasi.&gt;&gt;<bt>At the second feast, while they were drinking wine/grape juice (loan), the king again asked Ester saying, &lt;&lt;What is mother king's (=your) need/request? Whatever you want to request of me, na, just tell me/let me know! Cuz (elaboration) I'll give it Even if you request half of my wealth/the stuff of my kingdom, I will give (it).&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: cf. with wording in Ester 5:3.] [STYLE: It is respectful local style to address each other by rank.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vətinnaten lakh: it shall be given"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vətinnaten lakh: it shall be given to you.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vəteʕas: it shall be done"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vəteʕas: it shall be done</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais Ester manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini, bapa raja. Kalo bapa raja batúl-batúl sayang sang beta, deng mau kasi tunju rasa kasian sang beta, na, beta minta ko biar beta deng beta pung bangsa dong bisa idop. Beta pung parlú, andia itu.<bt>Then Ester responded saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, father king. If the king truly loves1 me, and wants to show love2/pity/mercy to me, na, I ask that you allow me and my race to be able to live That is what my need is.</bt><v n="4" />Te ada orang yang su jual buang sang beta deng beta pung bangsa dong, ko mau bunu bekin mati deng kasi ancor abis samua. Kalo dong cuma mau jual sang botong ko jadi budak, laki-laki deng parampuan, na, beta sonde omong sadiki ju, te beta sonde mau ganggu bapa raja deng parkara kici ana dong. Ma kalo bunu kasi abis sang beta deng beta pung orang dong, itu bekin rugi bésar sang bapa raja. Dia pung risiko tinggi na!&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) there is a person who has sold off/betrayed me and my race, in order to kill and totally destroy us all. If they only wanted to sell us-exc to become slaves, male and female, na, I wouldn't say even a little, cuz (elaboration) I don't want to bother/disturb father king with such small matters/issues/disputes. But as for killing off my and my people, that will cause a big/great/significant loss (financial/political) to father king. It has high risk (danger/safety/security/ financial/political/social) [+emphatic]!&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: cf. with 3:13.] [EXEG: last sentence in Heb vs. 4 possibly hardest verse in book to translate. 3 Heb words polysemous and obscure. See discussion in TN and TH. NLT and CEV ignore the Heb. clause, as recommended by Moffett. No consensus on how to handle it. We go in the direction of: annihilating the Jews would cause great loss/damage to the king/kingdom. -which is sort of what seems to be implied by NRSV and TB.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cr) We've translated &quot;a bother for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cr) We've translated "a bother for the king" (nezeq) rather than "the king is going to lose (nezeq) a lot money if he doesn't kill us Jews." Starlight says people are going to think that "No worry bout da money" in 3:11 means Haman doesn't have to pay. But with the "trouble" reading we can bypass the question of the money. And working into the text something of what is meant by the things that don't get said in a Near Eastern bargaining situation (the king seeming to turn down Haman's offer of a substantial contribution, but he really knows he's going to get it) boggles the mind.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Does the reader know that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">(cn) Does the reader know that here? In Chapter 4?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="CHECK: does rugi bésar default to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">CHECK: does rugi bésar default to financial, or can it also include social instability/riots?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niməkkarnuw (nif): we have been sold"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">niməkkarnuw (nif): we have been sold</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhashmiyd (nif inf): to be destroyed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhashmiyd (nif inf): to be destroyed</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lahərowg (hif): to kill"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">lahərowg (hif): to kill</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləʔabbed: (piʕel inf): to destroy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləʔabbed: (piʕel inf): to destroy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vəʔilluw: if - contrary to fact"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vəʔilluw: if - contrary to fact</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hechərashtiy (hif): I would have refrained"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hechərashtiy (hif): I would have refrained from speaking, acting</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsar: distress"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tsar: distress</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="showeh: be compared to. [BDB] Est"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">showeh: be compared to. [BDB] Est 7:4 (perhaps the hardest verse in this book to translate), "For would not this affliction (liquidation of the Jews) ʔamount to/be comparable toʔ a loss to the king?" or "for our affliction is not ʔto be comparedʔ to the king?"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nezeq: injury, damage, loss. (UBS) It"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nezeq: injury, damage, loss. (UBS) It may refer to damage in the sense of "damage to the empireʔs revenue," that is, financial loss. (2) It is understood by other interpreters to mean "trouble." The meaning then is "for our problem would not have been worth bothering [troubling] the king [about]" (so ab, FRCL, TOB). The translation by Gordis may be a good model based on this second interpretation: "for our distress would not have justified troubling the king." But at this point it sounds like sheʔs putting all the cards on the table, not just hinting. And not wanting to bother the king isnʔt a drastic enough reason for him to give such a fiery response in 5, whereas losing a major contribution to his treasury is. (The business earlier about "donʔt worry about the money" is parallel to the response in Genesis when Abraham is haggling down the atrociously high price for the burial cave in Hebron, and the seller says, "Iʔll give it to you, donʔt bother about the money." They both know Abraham is going to end up paying a lot.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of S section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ju raja Ahasuweros tanya sang dia pung bini Ester bilang, &lt;&lt;Hoe! Sapa yang mau bekin bagitu? Sapa yang barani bagitu tu?&gt;&gt;<bt>And so king Ahasuweros asked his wife Ester saying, &lt;&lt;Hoe [+problem]! Who wants to do that? Who would dare to do that? [+emphatic/demand]&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məlaʔow libbow: he has filled his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">məlaʔow libbow: he has filled his heart [more like "head"]</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ais Ester manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Itu orang jahat tu, andia Haman. Te dia yang bamusu deng botong, ko mau bunu bekin mati sang beta deng beta pung bangsa anteru!&gt;&gt;<bt>So Ester responded saying, &lt;&lt;That evil person is Haman. Cuz (elaboration) he is the one who is enemies/at enmity with us-exc, and wants to kill me and my entire race!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01286c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dengar Ester kasi tau dia pung jahat sang raja, pas di dia pung muka bagitu, ju Haman taku mau mati.<bt>Hearing Ester tell/explain his evil to the king right in front of him like that, Haman was terrified.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nivʕat (bʕt nif): was terrified"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nivʕat (bʕt nif): was terrified</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ma raja talalu mara. Andia ko dia badiri, jalan kasi tenga sang dong. Dia jalan pi istana pung taman ko pikir mau bekin karmana.<bt>But the king was too angry. That is why he stood up and left them behind. He went to the palace garden (not food)/park to think what/how to do. [EXEG: ‘feast’ and ‘wine’ made implicit (to not skew the focus, which in RL should be on the people); purpose of going to garden made explicit, see TN.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qam: stood up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">qam: stood up</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chəmatow: in his rage"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chəmatow: in his rage</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ginnat: garden"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ginnat: garden</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ma Haman lia kalo raja su mau kasi ancor buang sang dia, ais dia tenga di situ ko mau minta sang Ester kasi salamat sang dia.<bt>But Haman saw that the king was going to destroy him (totally), so he remained there to request Ester to save/rescue him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raʔah: he saw"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">raʔah: he saw</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khaltah: be completed, finished; to be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">khaltah: be completed, finished; to be prepared, made ready</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Itu waktu, Ester ada baring-baring di korsi panjang ko makan pesta, iko dong pung biasa. Pas waktu raja maso kambali dari taman pi dalam tampa makan pesta tu, ju dia lia Haman ada buang badan ko pegang Ester pung kaki ko minta raja pung bini kasi salamat sang dia.<bt>At that time, Ester was layingdown/reclining on a long chair to eat the feast, according to their norms (normal ways of doing things). Just when the king came back in from the garden/park into place of eating the feast, he saw Haman throwing himself to hold Ester's feet/legs to ask the king's wife to save/rescue him. [EXEG-1: very tricky to get the right dynamics that are faithful to the Heb semantics, faithful to the context, faithful to Haman's purpose, and faithful to what the king thought he saw and accused Haman of in next part of verse.] [EXEG-2: CEV uses European symbolic action of ‘kneeling’ to plead, but that doesn't really set up the king's accusation of “assaulting the queen”. the Heb. nofel ‘falling (or throwing himself down) as a suppliant’ evokes in the Middle East or Timor the symbolic action of throwing oneself down and grasping the lower legs to beg for help/mercy. I've seen it. I've experienced it. And it has been described that way to me in many local lgs and stories. This picture resonates much better with the king's accusation.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nofel (partcpl): there was Haman, falling"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nofel (partcpl): there was Haman, falling (or throwing himself down) as a suppliant</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miTTah: couch"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">miTTah: couch</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lia bagitu, ju raja maruak bilang, &lt;&lt;Hoe! Ini orang su talalu! Te dia barani mau parkosa sang beta pung bini di beta pung ruma sandiri ni!&gt;&gt;<bt>Seeing that, the king became fed up/furious saying, &lt;&lt;Hoe [+problem]! This man is too much (gone beyond what is acceptable/crossed the line)! Cuz (elaboration) he dares to try to rape my wife in my own house here!&gt;&gt; [EXEG: violate, molest, rape, sexual assault. TWOT, TN, CEV, TH, TB, BIS]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="likhbowsh (inf): molest (a woman); sexual"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">likhbowsh (inf): molest (a woman); sexual abuse</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dengar raja omong bagitu, ju dia pung pagawe dong tutu ame Haman pung muka pake kaen. Itu jadi tanda bilang dia musti mati.<bt>Hearing the king speak like that, his officials covered Haman's face with a cloth. That was a sign that he must die. [EXEG: ‘cover’ and purpose following HCE, TN, and TH, even though TH waffles all over the place on this.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chafuw: they covered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chafuw: they covered</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ais raja pung orang parcaya satu yang layani sang dia, nama Harbona, usul bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa raja. Masi ada itu tiang gantong di Haman pung muka ruma. Dia pung tinggi 22 meter, ko biar samua orang bisa dapa lia. Te Haman mau pake itu tiang ko gantong bekin mati sang Mordekai, andia itu orang yang su kasi salamat sang bapa raja dolu, waktu itu dua orang mau bunu sang bapa raja.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then one of the king's trusted people who served him, named Harbona, suggested saying, &lt;&lt;Father king. There is still that hanging pole in front of Haman's house. It is 22 meters tall, so that everyone can see. Cuz (elaboration) Haman wanted to use that pole to hang to death Mordekai, that is the person who saved father king previously when those two people wanted to kill father king.&gt;&gt; [NOTE to daughter translations: cf. with 5:14.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔechad min haSSariySiym: one from the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔechad min haSSariySiym: one from the group of eunuchs (plural)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dengar bagitu, ju raja suru bilang, &lt;&lt;Hoo. Pi gantong sang Haman di situ su!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that, the king order saying, &lt;&lt;Hoo [+agreement]. Go hang Haman there [+imperative]!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gam hinneh: as a matter of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">gam hinneh: as a matter of fact, you know what? Attention on the current action.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təluhuw (imperv pl): hang him!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">təluhuw (imperv pl): hang him!</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ais dong gantong bekin mati sang Haman di itu tiang yang dia sandiri su bekin ko siap mau bunu sang Mordekai di situ. Bunu abis, ju raja pung hati jadi dingin.<bt>So then they hung to death Haman on that pole that he himself had made to be ready to kill Mordekai there. After killing (him), the king's liver became cool (=anger abated/dissapated).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hekhiyn (kwn hif): he had erected"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hekhiyn (kwn hif): he had erected</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shakhakhah (shkk): abated"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">shakhakhah (shkk): abated</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of P section</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ester cari jalan ko kasi salamat dia pung orang Yahudi dong<bt>Ester looks for a way to save her Yahudi people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="8" />
      <v n="1" />Itu hari ju, raja Ahasuweros sarakan Haman pung harta samua pi dia pung bini Ester, te Haman tu yang bamusu deng Ester pung bangsa Yahudi. Itu waktu ju Mordekai datang mangada di raja, ais Ester buka kartu kalo dia bakelu deng Mordekai.<bt>That same day king Ahasuweros turned over all of Haman's belongings/possessions to his wife Ester, cuz (elaboration) that Haman was the one who was enemies with Ester's Yahudi race. At that time also Mordekai came before theking, and then Ester revealed the secret/what was unknown (idiom: opened/revealed the card) that she was family/related to Mordekai.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsorer (partcpl): the one hostile"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tsorer (partcpl): the one hostile</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ais ju raja ame dia pung cincin stempel dari dia pung jari sandiri yang dia su dapa kambali dari Haman, ais sarakan kasi sang Mordekai. Ju Ester angka Mordekai ko urus Haman pung harta deng tana milik dong.<bt>Then the king took his signet ring from his own finger which he had gotten back from Haman, and handed it over to Mordekai. And Ester elevated/appointed Mordekai to handle/manage Haman's possessions and land/s.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyaSar (Swr hif): he put away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyaSar (Swr hif): he put away</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Tabbaʕtow: his seal-ring, signet ring for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">Tabbaʕtow: his seal-ring, signet ring for stamping wax or clay seals on papers</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heʕəviyr (hif): he had gotten back"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">heʕəviyr (hif): he had gotten back</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais satu kali lai, Ester maso pi raja pung ruang parenta ko mau ba'omong deng raja. Ju dia tikam lutut di raja pung kaki, deng manangis ko mau minta raja cari jalan ko biar Haman, yang orang Agag tu, pung rancana jahat jang jadi.<bt>Then one more time Ester entered into the king's governing room wanting to speak to the king. And she knelt at the king's feet, and wept wanting to ask/request the king to find a way so that Haman, that Agag person, his evil plan should not happen/come into being/fruition. [EXEG: Heb. ‘she repeated/again’ signals a new scene. TH, NLT. We read the TAM here as vs.3 is purpose/intent; vs. 4 is opportunity granted; vs.5 is actual request. Therefore, going to direct quote as CEV in vs.3 introduces confusion. Heb discourse possibility of a 2-pass overlay is difficult to mirror in these RLs without making a verse bridge of 3-5 and conflating info. NOTE: the law of the Medes and the Persians cannot be /batal/ ‘cancelled’ or /cabut/ ‘withdrawn’ (see Est. 8:8 and book of Daniel), so we avoid using those terms. (TB uses /dibatalkan/, but Ester would have known that is not possible.) NRSV ‘avert’ is a very careful and deliberate way around this. Heb is ‘cause to pass into nothingness, come to naught’.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vattitchannen: she prayed for mercy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vattitchannen: she prayed for mercy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhaʕəviyr (hif): to cause to pass"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhaʕəviyr (hif): to cause to pass (into nothingness)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="machshavtow: his thought, device, invention"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">machshavtow: his thought, device, invention</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01282c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Lia bagitu, ju raja sorong dia pung tongkat parenta mas yang ada di dia pung tangan ko kasi tunju bilang, dia mau tarima bae sang Ester.<bt>Seeing (her) like that, the king extended/stretched out his gold ruling staff/scepter which was in his hand, to indicate that he wated to accept/receive Ester. [NOTE: differences in versification at end of vs.4 and beginning of vs. 5. See discussion in TH. We follow TB, NLT.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyowsheT (yshT hif): he held out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyowsheT (yshT hif): he held out</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ais Ester badiri di raja pung muka,<bt>So then Esther stood in front of the king,</bt><v n="5" />ju bilang, &lt;&lt;Bapa raja yang mulia. Kalo bapa ada suka sang beta, deng kalo beta pung minta ni bacocok deng bapa raja pung suka, na, beta minta bagini: tolong tulis surat parenta yang tarek kambali itu surat-surat yang Haman, andia Hamedata pung ana, su parná tulis dong. Andia itu surat yang suru orang bunu bekin abis samua orang bangsa Yahudi dalam bapa raja pung 127 propinsi dong.<bt>and said, &lt;&lt;Most glorious father king [NOTE: patterning on literary Malay]. If father  (=you) like/are pleased with me, and if my request fits/matches conforms to father king's liking, na, I request like this: please write a letter of command/law which pulls back those letters that Haman, that is Hamedata's child, has written. That is those letters that order people to kill of all the people of the Yahudi race within father king's 127 provinces. [DISCOURSE: Agag in vs. 3. Too heavy info load in RL background-foreground patterns, so explicit to implicit here as in CEV.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="khasher: it is right"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">khasher: it is right</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləʔabbed (piʕel inf): to destroy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləʔabbed (piʕel inf): to destroy</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Te beta sonde bisa tahan ame lia calaka yang nanti jato kaná di beta pung orang dong sampe dong ancor abis. Apalai beta pung kelu sandiri dong. Beta sonde kuat bagitu, bapa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I couldn't stand it/endure to see the calamity/misfortune fall on my people to the point that they are completely destroyed. Especially even my own family/relatives. I am not strong in that way, father.&gt;&gt; [DISCOURSE: last sentence adds emphasis, reflecting 2nd RQ in the Heb.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔeykhakhah: how in the world? (implying"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔeykhakhah: how in the world? (implying itʔs impossible)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔuwkhal (ykl): shall I endure?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔuwkhal (ykl): shall I endure?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔavden: destruction"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔavden: destruction</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mowladtiy: my family"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mowladtiy: my family</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7-8" />Ju raja Ahasuweros kasi tau sang Ester deng Mordekai bilang, &lt;&lt;Ma inga te, dia pung susa bagini: kalo ada surat parenta yang kaluar bawa raja pung nama deng pake cap dari raja pung cincin stempel, na, itu parenta sonde bisa batal deng sonde bisa cabu kambali. Ma orang dong su tau bilang, beta su suru gantong bekin mati sang Haman. Deng beta ju su sarakan Haman pung harta milik samua di Ester pung tangan, tagal Haman bamusu deng bangsa Yahudi deng ator siasat ko mau kasi ancor abis sang dong. Ais beta su kasi raja pung cincin stempel sang Mordekai. Jadi bosong bisa tulis apa sa, iko bosong pung suka so'al ini parkara deng orang Yahudi dong. Inga te, bosong tulis apa pake raja pung cincin stempel, na, orang sonde bisa cabu kambali. Te itu sama ke beta yang su parenta bagitu!<bt>Then king Ahasuweros told/explained to Ester and Mordekai saying, &lt;&lt;But you must remember that there is this difficulty: if there is a letter with a command/order that has gone out bearing the king's name and using the stamp/symbol from the king's signet ring, na, that command cannot be cancelled and cannot be withdrawn/revoked. But the people know that I have ordered Haman to be hung to death. And I have also turned over all of Haman's possessions/wealth into queen Ester's hands, because Haman was enemies with the Yahudi race/people/ethnic group and plotted to completely destroy them. So I have given the king's [yes, kings would refer to themselves using 3s] signet ring to Mordekai. So (consequently), you-pl can write whatever, following your desire about this issue/matter/dispute over the Yahudi (pl). Remember, whatever you write using the king's signet ring, na, people cannot withdraw/revoke it. Cuz (elaboration) that is the same as if I am the one who commanded like that! [DISCOURSE: reframed to convey the complexity of the dilemma below.] [EXEG: TN discusses whether reminder of the law is a) a general statement covering both Haman's and later Mordekai's letters [a possible reading of BHS, NRSV, NLT and TB], b) Haman's earlier letter, or c) Mordekai's letter to be written. We take it as both (a), and here specifically including Haman's letter (as minority TEV view), because the content of Mordekai's letter below in 11-13 is taking it as given that Haman's earlier letter cannot be revoked and will be followed, but still provides a clever way out (the Jews can defend themselves when attacked, and can even counterattack--with the blessing of the king). If it were giving total authority to Mordekai, he would simply cancel Haman's earlier letter--which is something that cannot be done in the laws of the Medes and Persians. I think the versions that try to imply that Xerxes is giving authority to Mordecai to cancel or withdraw Haman's letter are incorrect AND misunderstand the complexity of the bind they are in. The king can't figure out a workable solution--it is up to Ester and Mordekai.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chitmu (imperv): seal a document"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chitmu (imperv): seal a document</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01288c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Jadi itu waktu ju, andia tanggal 25 Juni,<bt>So (consequently), that same time, that is 25th June,</bt><note reference="8:9" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;hari ka-23 dalam bulan ka-tiga, andia bulan <span class="Italic">Siwan.&gt;&gt;</span> Iko kotong pung kalendar sakarang, itu hari jato kaná di tanggal 25 Juni, taon 474 SM (Sebelum Masehi). Tulisan bahasa Ibrani ju tulis bilang &lt;&lt;Kus&gt;&gt;, andia sakarang jadi negara Sudan deng Etiopia bagian utara.<bt>The Ibrani language Bible wrote saying, &lt;&lt;the 23rd day in the third month, that is the month of <span class="Italic">Siwan.&gt;&gt;</span> Following our-inc calendar now, that day falls on 25 June, the year 474 SM (Before Messiah). The Ibrani language writings also wrote saying &lt;&lt;Kus&gt;&gt;, that is nowadays the countryof Sudan and Etiopia's northern part/s.</bt></note>Mordekai suru raja pung juru tulis dong datang bakumpul. Dong tulis surat parenta, iko parsís apa yang Mordekai kasi tau sang dong. Itu surat dong, dong tulis kasi samua-samua, andia: orang Yahudi, pagawe, gubernor, deng bangsawan dong di 127 propinsi yang tasiar dari Hindia sampe deng Sudan. Dong tulis iko tiap propinsi deng bangsa pung bahasa deng huruf dong. Dong tulis sang orang Yahudi pake dong pung bahasa Ibrani deng huruf Ibrani ju.<bt>Mordekai ordered the king's scribes to gather together. They wrote a letter of command/law, following exactly what Mordekai told them. Those letter, they wrote to everybody, that is: the Yahudi people, the officials, the governors, and the nobility in the 127 provinces spread out from Hindia (India) up to and including Sudan. They wrote according to each province and race's language and letters/script. They wrote to the Yahudi people using their Ibrani language and Ibrani letters/script too. [EXEG: see NLT and note for date. Who summoned secretaries? See TN discussion noting that Mordekai now had authority to do this. For ‘Sudan’ see note at 1:1.] [NOTE to daughter translations: compare with your terms and phrasing in 1:3 and 3:12.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyiqqarʔuw (nif): they were summoned"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyiqqarʔuw (nif): they were summoned</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəchashdarpəniym: satraps (leaders over the district"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔəchashdarpəniym: satraps (leaders over the district governors)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pachowt: governors of provinces"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">pachowt: governors of provinces</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hodduw: India"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hodduw: India</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kətavah vəʕam vaʕam kilshonow: in the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">kətavah vəʕam vaʕam kilshonow: in the writing system for every people according to their language</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Mordekai susun itu surat dong sama ke kalo raja Ahasuweros sandiri yang susun. Tiap surat yang mau kaluar bawa raja pung nama, deng tanda cap dari raja pung cincin stempel sandiri yang dia su sarakan kasi sang Mordekai tu. Ju dia kasi sang tukang bawa pasán dong ko nae kuda yang paling capát, yang dong piara kasi sang raja deng maksud bagitu.<bt>Mordekai composed those letters just as if it was king Ahasuweros himself who wrote (them). Each letter that was going to go out bore the king's name, and the sign of his stamp from the king's own signet ring that he had turned over to Mordekai. And he had the messengers (those who habitually took messages/instructions) mount/ride the fastest horses, which they raised for the king with that purpose.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ratsiym: runners. SK &quot;like Paul Revere.&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ratsiym: runners. SK "like Paul Revere."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rokhvey: riders of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">rokhvey: riders of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rekhesh: horse"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">rekhesh: horse</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəchashtəraniym (pl): royal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔəchashtəraniym (pl): royal</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rammakhiym: runners, mares"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">rammakhiym: runners, mares</Message></Annotation><v n="11-13" />Ini surat dong pung bunyi bagini:<bt>These letter's sound was like this: [NOTE: natural collocation.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Bapa raja kasi tau samua orang bagini:<bt>&lt;&lt;Father king tells/declares/explains to all people like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nanti taon muka, tanggal 7 Maret,<bt>Next year, on 7 Maret, [EXEG: NLT, see also 3:7.]</bt><note reference="8:11-13" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, hari ka-13 dari bulan 12, andia bulan <span class="Italic">Adar.</span> Iko kotong pung kalendar sakarang, itu hari jato kaná di tanggal 7 Maret. Lia ju Ester 3:7.<bt>The Ibrani language Bible writes saying, the 13th day of the 12th month, that is the month of <span class="Italic">Adar.</span> According to our calendar nowadays, that day fell on 7 Maret. See also Ester 3:7. [EXEG: cf. 3:7]</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">samua orang Yahudi di tiap kota di samua propinsi,<bt>all Yahudi people in each cityin every province,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">bole bakumpul, deng bole bela diri.<bt>may (have permission to) gather together and may defend themselves.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Kalo ada tantara yang sarbú datang di dong, na,<bt>If there is an army/s who come and attack them, na,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sarbú datang diff from datang sarbú"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z">sarbú datang diff from datang sarbú</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">orang Yahudi bole kasi ancor abis sang dong.<bt>the Yahudi people may (have permission to) completely destroy them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Kalo ada musu dari bangsa mana, ko, propinsi apa sa yang datang saráng sang dong, na,<bt>If there are enemies from whatever people/race, or, whatever province who come attack2 them, na,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">orang Yahudi bole balas kasi ancor sang dong kambali.<bt>the Yahudi people may reciprocate in turn and destroy them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Biar laki-laki ko parampuan.<bt>Whether male or female.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Biar orang kici ko orang bésar.<bt>Whether small/insignificant or big/important. [EXEG: local RL equivalent categories.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Bukan sa dong bole bela diri deng sarbú bale,<bt>Not only may they defend themselves and attack back,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ma orang Yahudi dong bole rampas ame dong pung musu pung harta milik deng tana milik samua ju.<bt>but the Yahudi people may rob/snatch/take their enemies' entire belongings and land as well.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ini surat parenta musti tempel di tiap propinsi,<bt>This letter of command/law must be posted in each province,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko biar samua orang bisa baca sandiri dalam dong pung bahasa sandiri.<bt>so that all people can read for themselves in their own language.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Deng bagitu orang Yahudi samua bisa siap memang.<bt>In that way the all Yahudi people can be prepared ahead of time.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Beta pung surat parenta bagitu sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>My letter of command/law is thus!&gt;&gt; [DISCOURSE: natural RL closure.] [EXEG: Q: Was this last bit part of the letter or just a comment on the letter? A: The Heb is ambiguous in the nifal form “is/was to be given”. LXX and CEV take this as part of the edict. Indonesian TB can be read either way but it seems more natural to read it as part of the edict. By noise of the English tense, it appears NRSV, NLT, and NIV assume it is a narrator's comment, but that is not clear either. It structures nicely in the RL discourse as part of the edict, so we go with the support of LXX, CEV (and TB) here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhiqqahel (nif inf): to assemble"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhiqqahel (nif inf): to assemble</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="laʕəmod: stand by, defend; stand firm,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">laʕəmod: stand by, defend; stand firm, remain, endure; resist</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nafsham: their lives"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nafsham: their lives</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhashmiyd: to destroy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhashmiyd: to destroy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cheyl: power, wealth, force, army"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">cheyl: power, wealth, force, army</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsariym (tswr partcpl pl): showing hostility"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tsariym (tswr partcpl pl): showing hostility</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Taf: children; those not fit to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">Taf: children; those not fit to march, including women, children, and elderly people</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəlalam: their spoil, prey, booty; gain"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">shəlalam: their spoil, prey, booty; gain</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="labowz (bzz inf): to take booty"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">labowz (bzz inf): to take booty</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhinnaten (nif): to be given"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhinnaten (nif): to be given</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dat: as orders"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">dat: as orders</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="galuwy (partcpl pass): to be uncovered,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">galuwy (partcpl pass): to be uncovered, made known</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕtwdym (partcpl pass ʕətudiym): ready, prepared"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕtwdym (partcpl pass ʕətudiym): ready, prepared</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhinnaqem (nqm nif): to be avenged"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhinnaqem (nqm nif): to be avenged</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01289c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ais ju raja suru tukang bawa pasán dong ko lari capát. Andia ko dong nae raja pung kuda yang paling capát dong, ais lari tasiar pi samua tampa, mulai dari benteng di kota Susa.<bt>Then the king ordered the messengers to run quickly. That is why they mounted the fastest of the king's horses, and ran in all directions to all places, beginning from the fort in the city of Susa.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məvohaliym (puʕal): urged on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">məvohaliym (puʕal): urged on</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dəchuwfiym (partcpl passive pl): done in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">dəchuwfiym (partcpl passive pl): done in haste</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ais ju waktu Mordekai kaluar dari raja pung istana, dia pake pakean yang biru deng puti, sama ke raja biasa pake. Dia pake topi jabatan dari mas, deng baju panjang dari kaen lenan dari Masir yang ada hias deng warna ungu. Waktu orang kota Susa dengar itu parkara pung jalan kaluar, deng lia Mordekai pung pakean alus, ju dong batarea rame-rame deng hati sanáng.<bt>After that, when Mordekai went our from the king's palace, he wore clothes that were blue and white, like the king normally wore. He wore a hat of rank/position from gold, and a long shirt/robe from lenan cloth from Masir (Egypt) which was decorated with purple colour. When the people of the city of Susa heard that solution (way out) to that matter/issue/dispute, and saw Mordekai's fine/expensive clothes, they shouted festively with happy livers. [EXEG: the Heb word is not just linen, but prized Egyptian linen. Ambiguity: some translations connect the rejoicing to the decree, while the Heb grammar seems to imply it links to Mordekai appearing in his finery, and this is reflected in other translations. We link both, as seems to be permitted by the Heb grammar. They are celebrating a clever solution to an apparently unsolvable dilemma--and celebrating the man who found the impossible and unexpected solution.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təkhelet: wool, dyed with violet purple-dye,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">təkhelet: wool, dyed with violet purple-dye, gained from the purple-gland of certain Murex-snails; təkhelet and ʔargaman both refer to colors that spanned the spectrum from brilliant red through deep purple, and "blue" is simply a conventional translation of teke4let.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chuwr: white"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chuwr: white</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕəTeret: crown"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕəTeret: crown</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="takhriykh: robe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">takhriykh: robe</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="buwts: fancy white linen from Egypt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">buwts: fancy white linen from Egypt</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔargaman: wool dyed with red purple"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔargaman: wool dyed with red purple</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsahəlah: shrill yelling"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tsahəlah: shrill yelling</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="samechah: rejoiced"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">samechah: rejoiced</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Waktu orang Yahudi dong dengar ada jalan kaluar bagitu, na, dong talalu sanáng, te dong bisa salamat, deng orang laen dong kasi tunju hormat sang dong.<bt>When the Yahudi people heard there was a solution like that, na, they were very/overly happy, cuz (elaboration) they could be saved, and other people could/were showing honour/respect to them. [EXEG: Heb ‘light’ is associated with life and prosperity (TWOT, TH). We reflect this as ‘relief, a way out (of the fix)’ and ‘life, salvation (from certain disaster)’]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔowrah: prosperity"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔowrah: prosperity</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sason: joy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">sason: joy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="viyəqar: and honor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">viyəqar: and honor</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Andia ko di tiap kota di samua propinsi, kalo raja pung surat parenta su sampe, na, samua orang Yahudi rasa sanáng. Ju dong bekin hari bae ko bapesta rame-rame. Ada orang laen ju yang minta dong angka sang dong jadi orang Yahudi ju, tagal dong taku orang Yahudi mau bekin apa-apa sang dong.<bt>That is why in each city in every province, if/when the king's letter of command/law had arrived, na, every Yahudi person felt happy. And they made a holiday/special day and feasted festively There were other/different people who requested that they be elevated/adopted to become Yahudi people too, because they were afraid the Yahudi people would do something/anything to them. [EXEG: this last sentence is safe middle ground--NRSV, NLT, CEV, HCE, TB; JEG &amp; TH note this word could also mean ‘declared themselves Jews’; BART says this form of the Heb. verb is sometimes used of feigning an action, so in this context it could mean ‘pretending to be Jews’.] [CHECK: would this be better rendered as “maso jadi orang Yahudi”?]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maggiyaʕ (ngʕ hif partcpl): arriving"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">maggiyaʕ (ngʕ hif partcpl): arriving</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishteh: party, celebration"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mishteh: party, celebration</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mityahədiym (yhd hitp): declared themselves Jews"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mityahədiym (yhd hitp): declared themselves Jews</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nafal: fell"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nafal: fell</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pachad: trembling, dread"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">pachad: trembling, dread</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Orang Yahudi kasi kala dong pung musu<bt>The Yahudi people defeat their enemies</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="9" />
      <v n="1" />Ais, tanggal 7 Maret ada dua parenta yang bawa raja pung nama, yang sah di itu hari. Jadi itu hari orang Yahudi pung musu dong baharap dong bisa kasi ancor buang orang Yahudi dong. Padahal itu hari ju, su jadi tabale, te su oba ko jadi hari yang orang Yahudi dong bisa kasi kala bale sang dong pung musu dong.<bt>So then on 7 Maret there were two commands that bore the king's name, which were valid/legal on that day. So (consequently), on that day the Yahudi people's enemies hoped they could completely destroy the Yahudi people. Whereas in fact, on that same day, it happened the other way around, cuz (elaboration) it changed to become a day in which the Yahudi people could defeat in return/instead their enemies. [EXEG: NLT, TH also says two royal edicts in the king's name, one from Haman, and the second from Mordekai. Some translations package the role of the Jews as realis, which complicates things for vs. 2, unless it is a 2-pass overlay, or an editorial comment. We take it as an editorial comment and handle it as irrealis in vs. 1 (riding on the Heb “they had hoped X and Y”. We make it realis in vs. 2.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sibbəruw (piʕel): they had hoped"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">sibbəruw (piʕel): they had hoped</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lishlowT (inf): to overpower"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">lishlowT (inf): to overpower</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nahəfowkh (nif): be turned around, be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nahəfowkh (nif): be turned around, be changed</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sonʔeyhem"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">sonʔeyhem</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, hari ka-13 dari bulan 12, andia bulan <span class="Italic">Adar.</span> Iko kotong pung kalendar sakarang, itu hari jato kaná di tanggal 7 Maret. Lia ju Ester 3:7.<bt>The Ibrani language Bible writes saying, the 13th day of the 12th month, that is the month of <span class="Italic">Adar.</span> According to our calendar nowadays, that day fell on 7 Maret. See also Ester 3:7. [EXEG: cf. 3:7; 9:1; NLT]</bt></note><v n="2" />Ais, di samua kota dalam itu 127 propinsi yang raja Ahasuweros pegang parenta dong, orang Yahudi bakumpul saráng bale sang musu-musu dong yang mau kasi ancor buang sang dong. Sonde ada yang bisa lawan ame sang dong, te samua bangsa laen dong taku mati sang orang Yahudi dong.<bt>So then, in all cities in the 127 provinces in which king Ahasuweros held rule/governed, the Yahudi people gathered together and attacked back (against) their enemies who wanted to completely destroy them. There was nobody who could stand against/oppose (successfully-svc) them, cuz (elaboration) all the other races were terribly afraid of the Yahudi people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niqhəluw (nif): assembled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">niqhəluw (nif): assembled</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lishloach yad: to put out their"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">lishloach yad: to put out their hand, attack</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="məvaqshey raʕatam: that sought evil/harm for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">məvaqshey raʕatam: that sought evil/harm for them</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ais orang bésar samua di itu 127 propinsi, andia: pagawe istana, gubernor, deng bangsawan dong, cari jalan ko mau tolong orang Yahudi dong, te dong su taku sang Mordekai.<bt>So then all the big/important people in those 127 provinces, that is: palace officials, guvernors, and nobles, looked for ways to help the Yahudi people, cuz (elaboration) they were afraid of Mordekai. [NOTE to daughter translations: compare with terms used in 3:12 and 8:9.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mənassəʔiym (piʕel partcpl pl): care for,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mənassəʔiym (piʕel partcpl pl): care for, assist, help, support</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Te orang di itu 127 propinsi dong samua su tau bilang, raja su angka Mordekai di dia pung istana, ju dia pung nama su tasiar pi mana-mana. Deng dia pung kuasa batamba tarús.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) in those 127 provinces they all knew that the king had elevated/appointed Mordekai in his palace, and his name/reputation had spread everywhere. And his power/authority kept increasing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shamʕow: his reputation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">shamʕow: his reputation</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="howlekh (partcpl): was going"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">howlekh (partcpl): was going</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Jadi itu hari ju orang Yahudi dong pegang kalewang, ais bunu bekin mati deng kasi ancor buang sang orang yang bamusu deng dong. Dong bekin iko dong pung suka.<bt>So (consequently) that same day the Yahudi people took up/held/grabbed (fightng) swords, and killed and completely destroyed the people who were enemies/at enmity with them. They did whatever they liked.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vayyakkuw (nkh hif): they struck"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">vayyakkuw (nkh hif): they struck</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kat: blow, wound of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">kat: blow, wound of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hereg: slaughter"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hereg: slaughter</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔavden: act of destroying"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔavden: act of destroying</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="snəʔeyhem: their enemies, the ones that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">snəʔeyhem: their enemies, the ones that hate them</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rətsownam: their pleasure"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">rətsownam: their pleasure</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Dalam itu benteng di kota Susa sandiri sa, dong bunu bekin mati 500 orang.<bt>Within the fort in the city of Susa alone/itself, they killed 500 people. [EXEG: TH, NLT, RSV, TEV reflect the emphatic fronting in the Heb, here also as ‘itself’. Heb ‘men’ is rendered here as ‘people’, following discussion in TH, NRSV, CEV, TB, and RL patterns of talking about events of this sort.]</bt><v n="7-10" />Dong ju bunu bekin mati sang Haman pung sapulu ana laki-laki. Andia: Parsandata, Dalfon, Aspata, Porata, Adalya, Aridata, Parmasta, Arisai, Aridai, deng Waisata. (Haman tu, andia Hamedata pung ana, yang bamusu deng bangsa Yahudi tu.) Ma orang Yahudi dong sonde rampas orang pung harta sadiki ju.<bt>They also killed Haman's ten sons. That is: Parsandata, Dalfon, Aspata, Porata, Adalya, Aridata, Parmasta, Arisai, Aridai, and Waisata. (That Haman, was Hamedata's child, who was enemies with the Yahudi race.) But the Yahudi people did not rob/snatch/take even a little bit of people's belongings. [DISCOURSE: repackaged to follow natural RL packaging.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕəseret: ten"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕəseret: ten</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bizzah: booty, plunder"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">bizzah: booty, plunder</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Itu hari ju orang lapor sang raja, ko kasi tau bilang, &lt;&lt;Orang Yahudi dong su bunu abis barapa orang dalam benteng di ini kota Susa.&gt;&gt;<bt>That same day people reported to the king, and informed him saying, &lt;&lt;The Yahudi people have killed off a number of people in the fort here in the city of Susa.&gt;&gt; [DISCOURSE: made direct speech following RL preferred style in this region.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ais ju raja kasi tau sang Ester bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta su dengar bilang, orang Yahudi dong su bunu bekin mati 500 orang dalam ini benteng di kota Susa. Dong ju bunu kasi abis Haman pung ana laki-laki sapulu orang dong. Beta sonde bisa bayangkan dong su bekin karmana di propinsi yang laen dong. Ma beta mau tanya, mama raja masi ada parlú, ko? Mama raja minta apa sa, nanti beta bekin iko. Kasi tau sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>The the king told Ester saying, &lt;&lt;I have heard that the Yahudi people have killed 500 people in this fort in the city of Susa. They have alsokilled off Haman's ten sons. I cannot imagine what/how they have done in the other provinces. But I want to ask, does mother king have any other needs/requests/ Mother king can request anything, and I will do it. Just tell (me)!&gt;&gt; [EXEG: question about other provinces taken as RQ, and reframed as statement. See TN.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sshəʔelatekh: your request"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">sshəʔelatekh: your request</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕowd: duration, still"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕowd: duration, still</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ju Ester manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Kalo bapa raja tarima bae, na, beta minta bagini: kalo beso, biar orang Yahudi dalam ini kota Susa bekin iko tarús itu surat parenta yang ada pake kamaren. Deng biar ko orang gantong ame Haman pung ana laki-laki sapulu orang pung mayat dong, ko biar samua orang bisa dapa lia. Beta pung minta bagitu sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Ester responded saying, &lt;&lt;If father king accepts/is willing, na, I request like this: as for tomorrow, allow the Yehudi people within this city of Susa to continue to follow/obey that letter of command which was used/in effect/valid yesterday. And allow/permit people to hand Haman's ten sons' corpses, so that everyone may see (them). That is my (mere, trivialised) request.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: clause implied by social context, and made explicit by CEV “in public”, TN, TH.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitluw (tlh): may they hang them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yitluw (tlh): may they hang them</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ais raja tarima bae, ju dia kasi kaluar parenta di kota Susa, yang suru orang ko gantong ame Haman pung ana laki-laki sapulu orang pung mayat dong.<bt>Then the king accepted that, and issued a command in the city of Susa, which ordered people to hang the corpses of Haman's ten sons.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ju dia pung beso, andia tanggal 8 Maret, orang Yahudi dalam kota Susa bunu tamba 300 orang lai. Ma dong sonde rampas ame orang pung harta sadiki ju.<bt>On the following day, that is 8 Maret, the Yahudi people in the city of Susa killed an additional 300 people. But they did not rob/snatch/take even a little of people's belongings.</bt><note reference="9:15" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, hari ka-14 dari bulan <span class="Italic">Adar.</span> Iko kotong pung kalendar sakarang, itu hari jato kaná di tanggal 8 Maret.<bt>The Ibrani language Bible writes saying, the 14th day of the month of <span class="Italic">Adar.</span> According to our calendar nowadays, that day fell on the 8 Maret. [EXEG: cf. 3:7; 9:1; NLT]</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16-17" />Itu waktu ju, andia tanggal 7 Maret, orang Yahudi yang tenga dalam raja pung 127 propinsi yang laen dong bakumpul ko bela diri dari musu dong. Ju dong bunu bekin mati 75.000 orang. Deng bagitu, dong bisa rasa aman, te sonde ada yang ancam sang dong lai. Ma dong sonde rampas ame orang pung harta sadiki ju. Dia pung beso, andia tanggal 8 Maret, dong bekin pesta rame-rame, tagal sanáng.<bt>At that time, that is 7 Maret, Yahudi people who lived in the 127 other provinces gathered to defend themselves from their enemies. And they killed 75,000 people. In that way, they could feel safe, cuz (elaboration) there was nobody else who was threatening them anymore. But they did not rob/snatch/take even a little of people's belongings. The next day, that is 8 Maret, they made a celebratory feast, because they were happy. [EXEG-1: “defend themselves” needs to be read as allowing pre-emptive strikes in light of 8:11: “By these letters the king allowed the Jews who were in every city to assemble and defend their lives, to destroy, to kill, and to annihilate any armed force of any people or province that might attack them, with their children and women, and to plunder their goods.”] [EXEG-2: Verses bridged and new paragraph to reset time frame and location shift. See TH. See also discussion in TN, TH re: “gained relief from their enemies”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕamod ʕal-nafsham: they took a stand"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕamod ʕal-nafsham: they took a stand to save their lives</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nowach: rest, relief from their enemies"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nowach: rest, relief from their enemies</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Orang Yahudi bekin Pesta Purim yang partama<bt>The Yahudi people make the first Purim Feast</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Deng bagitu, tanggal 7 deng 8 Maret di kota Susa, orang Yahudi dong bakumpul dua hari ko baparáng lawan orang yang bamusu deng dong. Ma tanggal 9 Maret, dong barenti, ais dong bakumpul ko bapesta rame-rame.<bt>In that way, on 7 and 8 Maret in the city of Susa, the Yahudi people gathered together to war against the people who were their enemies. But on 9 Maret, they stopped, and they gathered to feast in celebration. [DISCOURSE: we take the Hebrew here as a recap, so use it to introduce the new pericope, as does NRSV. See also discussion in TH.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ma kalo orang Yahudi yang tenga di kampong-kampong deng kota laen, dong cuma baparáng satu hari sa. Andia ko sampe sakarang ju, tiap taon, andia tanggal 8 Maret,<bt>But as for the Yahudi people who lived in the villages and other cities, they only warred for one day. That is why to this day, every year, on 8 Maret,</bt><note reference="9:19" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab bahasa Ibrani tulis bilang, hari ka-14 dari bulan <span class="Italic">Adar.</span><bt>The Ibrani language Bible writes saying, the 14th day of the month of <span class="Italic">Adar.</span></bt></note>dong bakumpul ko bapesta rame-rame. Di itu hari bae, dong bakirim makanan kasi satu deng satu.<bt>they gather to feast in celebration. On that holiday, they send each other food. [NOTE to daughter translations: Many local lgs have a term for gifts of food sent home after a feast to symbolise generous hospitality. Check.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pərazowt: rural"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">pərazowt: rural</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕowiym ʔet yowm: they make that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕowiym ʔet yowm: they make that the day of rejoicing</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishlowach: sending"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mishlowach: sending</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="manowt: parts, portions. In other instances"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">manowt: parts, portions. In other instances (e.g. Hannah, Esther, Nehemiah), the distribution of "portions" indicates the unity of the family or community, and emphasizes the high regard the giver had for the recipient. Gifts of food.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Samua yang jadi tu, Mordekai tulis bae-bae. Ju dia kirim surat pi kasi samua orang Yahudi yang tenga di 127 propinsi yang raja Ahasuweros pegang parenta dong, biar jao ko dekat.<bt>Everything that happened, Mordekai wrote carefully. And he sent a letter/s to all the Yahudi people who lived in the 127 provinces in which king Ahasuweros held rule/governed, whether far or near.</bt><v n="21" />Dia tulis kasi tau sang dong bilang:<bt>He wrote telling them/informing them saying:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Mulai sakarang, tiap taon bosong musti bekin pesta yang jato di tanggal 8 deng 9 Maret.<bt>&lt;&lt;Beginning now, every year you-pl must make a feast which falls on 8 and 9 Maret.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləqayyem (piʕel inf): to confirm, establish"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləqayyem (piʕel inf): to confirm, establish</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Te itu dua hari tu, yang kotong orang Yahudi kasi kala abis sang orang yang bamusu deng kotong. Deng bagitu, kotong su barenti cape, te sonde kaná ancam lai, deng samua su roba jadi baru. Andia ko kotong musti inga ini bulan, te kotong pung susa su oba jadi sanáng, deng kotong pung duka su oba jadi pesta rame-rame. Kotong sonde idop deng taku deng manangis lai. Andia ko tiap taon kotong musti bekin pesta rame-rame. Kotong musti bakirim makanan kasi satu deng satu, ju kasi barang sang orang miskin dong.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) those two days, are the ones in which we-inc Yahudi people completely defeated the people who were enemies with us. In that way, we have found/attained rest (stop tiredness), cuz (elaboration) there is no longer any threat, and everything has changed to become new. That is why we must remember this month, cuz (elaboration) our-inc difficulty/trouble has changed to become happiness, and our grief has changed to become feasting in celebration. We do not live in fear and crying anymore. That is why every year we must make a celebration feast. We must send each other food, and also give things to the poor people.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nehəppakh (hpk nif): it was changed,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nehəppakh (hpk nif): it was changed, the situation turned around</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yagown: grief"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yagown: grief</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔevel: mourning"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔevel: mourning</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yowm Towv: holiday"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yowm Towv: holiday</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mattanowt: gifts"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mattanowt: gifts</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔevyowniym: poor, miserable people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔevyowniym: poor, miserable people</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Tarima itu surat yang Mordekai su tulis dong, ju orang Yahudi tarima bae, ais bekin hari bae tiap taon bagitu.<bt>(Upon) Receiving those letters that Mordekai wrote, the Yahudi people accepted/agreed with (the contents/suggestion), and so made a feast every year like that.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qibbel (piʕel): receive, take; accepted the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">qibbel (piʕel): receive, take; accepted the idea</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hechelluw (chll hif): they had begun"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hechelluw (chll hif): they had begun</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24-26" />Naa, dia pung carita kanapa dong kasi nama itu hari bae bilang <span class="Italic">&lt;&lt;Purim&gt;&gt;,</span> andia bagini: dolu, ada satu orang Agag, nama Haman, andia Hamedata pung anak. Dia yang ator siasat ko mau bunu bekin abis orang Yahudi dong samua. Tagal dia mau cari waktu yang pas ko bekin jadi dia pung akal jahat, andia ko dia hela lot ko pili dia pung hari yang paling bae ko mau bunu orang Yahudi dong. Naa, &lt;lot dong&gt; dalam bahasa Ibrani bilang, <span class="Italic">&lt;pur-im&gt;.</span> (Dia pung bentuk tunggal, andia <span class="Italic">&lt;pur&gt;.)</span> Ma waktu Ester dapa tau, ais pi mangada kasi tau sang raja, ju raja parenta pake surat bilang, itu rancana jahat yang Haman su ator ko bekin jahat sang orang Yahudi musti makan bale di Haman pung kapala sandiri. Te dia deng dia pung ana laki-laki dong samua musti mati tagantong di tiang. Itu, dia pung carita kanapa dong kasi nama itu hari bae bilang, &lt;&lt;Purim&gt;&gt;. Di itu hari bae dong inga samua yang jadi kaná deng orang Yahudi, ju dong inga itu surat yang Mordekai parná tulis yang kasi tunju jalan kaluar kasi sang dong.<bt>Naa [+shift], the story of why they named that feast saying, <span class="Italic">&lt;&lt;Purim&gt;&gt;,</span> is like this: long ago/previously, there was an Agag person named Haman, that is Hamedata's child. Heis the one who plotted to kill off all the Yahudi people. Because he wanted to find the best/most auspicious time to carry out his evil plan, thatis why he drew lots to choose the best day to kill the Yahudi people. Naa, [+shift] &lt;lots&gt; in the Ibrani language are called <span class="Italic">&lt;pur-im&gt;.</span> (Its singular form is <span class="Italic">&lt;pur&gt;.)</span> But when Ester found out, and then she went before the king to tell him, and king ordered by letter that the evil plan which Haman had arranged to do evil to the Yahudi people must eat back Haman's own head (=fall back on). Cuz (elaboration) he and his sons must all die hanging on a pole. That is the story why they named that feast &lt;&lt;Purim&gt;&gt;. On that holiday they remember everything that happened to/befell the Yahudi people, and they remember the letter that Mordekai had written which showed a/the way out/solution for them. [DISCOURSE: repackaged for RL as a background explanation.] [EXEG: make significance of letter explicit here--a workable solution to an apparently unresolvable dilemma.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="throw down small rocks fo pick"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">throw down small rocks fo pick</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chashav: made a plot, plan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">chashav: made a plot, plan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləʔabbədam (inf): to destroy them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləʔabbədam (inf): to destroy them</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hippiyl (npl hif): he caused to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">hippiyl (npl hif): he caused to fall (like throwing dice); in English we say "cast lots" for several different forms of determining a chance answer.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="puwr: lot. The word occurs only"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">puwr: lot. The word occurs only in the book of Esther 3:7; 9:24; 9:26 (two times), 28, 29, 31, 32. Hebrew pu=r is to be distinguished from go=ra4l, the usual word for "lot." In Est 3:7 and 9:24 the two words appear beside each other.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gowral: lot (Hebrew). Probably the noun"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">gowral: lot (Hebrew). Probably the noun is related to Arabic g]arwal "pebble" (KB) and by metonomy came to be used for "lot" because little stones were used in lasting lots. BDB call attention here to Greek pse4phos = "pebble," "vote," and kuamos = "bean," "lot." It refers then to some article like a stone which was thrown or allowed to fall in a way to determine a choice. In some cases not only the lot itself but what was chosen is called lot (Jud 1:3), and oneʔs circumstances or even life as a whole is oneʔs lot (Ps 16:5).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləhummam (hmm): to confuse, disturb; break,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləhummam (hmm): to confuse, disturb; break, consume, crush, destroy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʕim-haSSefer: by means of a written"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʕim-haSSefer: by means of a written document</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔiggeret: letter"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔiggeret: letter</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kakhah: thus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">kakhah: thus</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="higgiyaʕ (ngʕ hif): that had happened"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">higgiyaʕ (ngʕ hif): that had happened to them, touched them, reached them</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Ester 3:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Mulai dari itu waktu, orang Yahudi dong bekin hari bae yang jalan dua hari ko inga itu parkara. Dong bekin bagitu tarús tiap taon. Itu jadi dong pung biasa tiap taon, iko samua yang Mordekai su tulis kasi sang dong, sampe turun-tamurun.<bt>Beginning from that time, the Yahudi people make a holiday which goes two days to remember that event/issue/matter/dispute. They continue to do like that every year. That has become their norm/custom every year, following everything that Mordekai had written to them, on until their descendents [NOTE: grammar and lexicon are ongoing without end point here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zarʕam: their offspring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">zarʕam: their offspring</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nilwiym (lwh nif): those joined to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nilwiym (lwh nif): those joined to them</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zmannam: their fixed time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">zmannam: their fixed time</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Dia pung batúl, andia: dalam tiap generasi, tiap kelu orang Yahudi di tiap kota di tiap propinsi, musti inga itu parkara deng bekin iko itu hari bae Purim tu. Sonde bole putus, ma musti kasi jalan tarús bagitu sampe turun-tamurun.<bt>Actually/theright thing is this: in each generation, every family of Yahudi people in each city in each province, must remember that matter/issue/dispute and do according to that Purim holiday. It may not cease, but must continue on through ongoing generations.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nizəkkariym (nif): be remembered, not be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nizəkkariym (nif): be remembered, not be forgotten</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dowr vadowr: generation to generation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">dowr vadowr: generation to generation</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishpachah uwmishpachah: clan to clan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mishpachah uwmishpachah: clan to clan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mədiynah: province, district"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mədiynah: province, district</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="viymey happuwriym haʔelleh: these days of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">viymey happuwriym haʔelleh: these days of Purim</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaʕavruw: they should not pass away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yaʕavruw: they should not pass away</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zikhram: their remembrance; name (by which"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">zikhram: their remembrance; name (by which one is remembered); praise, celebration</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaSuwf (Swp): it should not come"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">yaSuwf (Swp): it should not come to an end</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zarʕam: their offspring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">zarʕam: their offspring</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Jadi waktu Mordekai tulis dia pung surat nomer dua tu, raja pung bini Ester, andia Abihail pung ana, ju tulis satu surat yang bawa dia pung nama deng pangkat sandiri, yang dukung kuat Mordekai pung surat yang kasi jalan hari bae Purim tu.<bt>So (consequently) when Mordekai wrote his second letter, the king's wife Ester, that is Abihail's child, also wrote a letter bearing her own name and rank, which strongly supported Mordekai's letter that enacted the Purim festival.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="toqef: strength. The noun refers to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">toqef: strength. The noun refers to the "power" or "authority" of a kingdom (Dan 11:17) or a ruler (Est 9:29; 10:2).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ləqayyem: to establish, confirm"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ləqayyem: to establish, confirm</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sheniyt: second"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">sheniyt: second</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Ju ada surat-surat yang orang kirim kasi sang orang Yahudi yang tenga di itu 127 propinsi yang raja Ahasuweros pegang parenta dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Biar ko bosong samua bisa idop aman, dame, deng tanáng.&gt;&gt;<bt>And there were letters that people sent to the Yahudi people who lived in the 127 provinces in which king Ahasuweros held rule/governed saying, &lt;&lt;May all of you-pl live in security, relational peace, and inner calm.&gt;&gt; [EXEG-1: unpacking different aspects of Heb. <span class="Italic">shalowm</span>.] [EXEG-2: Q: In English this sounds like some other people than Ester and Mordekai. Is this just BT noise? A: See TH and NET note discussion of different ways of interpreting the Heb grammar here plus textual differences. (They note NIV is in a minority here.) We took it as impersonal passive. One reading: vs. 29: Esther wrote a letter in support of Mordekai's letter; vs. 30: other letters were sent (not clear by whom) wishing shalom; vs. 31 these (vs.30) letters also explained that they should do Purim in accord with Mordekai and Esther's letters. HCE is clearly this way. NRSV, NLT, NET and TB could all be read this way. However, the Heb 3s (impersonal) subject messes with that, since one would expect 3p if that were the case. So CEV (copies were sent) and NIV (Mordekai sent), the latter following a minority text, are not unreasonable.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shalowm: intact state; unconcern, ease; prosperity;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">shalowm: intact state; unconcern, ease; prosperity; welfare, condition; peace; friendship; peace, salvation</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔəmet: This word carries underlying sense"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔəmet: This word carries underlying sense of certainty, dependability.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ini surat dong ju kasi tau karmana dong musti bekin itu hari bae Purim tiap taon, iko Mordekai deng Ester dong pung surat. Orang Yahudi, dong pung ana, dong pung cucu, dong pung cece, deng dong pung turunan samua musti inga deng bekin itu hari bae tiap taon tarús-tarús, sama deng dong bekin orang Yahudi pung hari-hari bae laen dong ju. Ada yang dong makan rame-rame, ada yang dong musti puasa, deng ada yang dong musti manyasal deng sambayang minta tolong.<bt>These letters also explained how they must make the Purim holiday every year, according to Mordekai and Ester'sletters. The Yahudi people, their children, their grandchildren, their great-grandchildren, and all their descendants must remember and make that holiday every year continually, just like they make other Yahudi holidays. There are those in which they eat festively, there are those in which they must fast, and there are those in which they must regret/feel remorse/repent and pray asking for help. [EXEG: ‘lamentations, mourning’ Heb = ‘crying out for help’; TN = ‘pleading with God, not mourning the dead’]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nafsham: their souls; with the pronoun"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">nafsham: their souls; with the pronoun it means "took it upon themselves."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsomot: times of fasting (these are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">tsomot: times of fasting (these are not in connection with Purim itself, but refer to other occasions when the community took upon itself the responsibility of fasting and lamenting)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zaʕəqatam: their crying out for help."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">zaʕəqatam: their crying out for help. Mordecai gave this cry when he heard of Hamanʔs plot against the Jews (Est 4:1).</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Raja pung bini Ester pung parenta kasi tunju cara bekin hari bae Purim, deng suru dong bekin bagitu tiap taon. Dong ju tulis itu samua-samua di pamarenta pung buku sajara.<bt>The king's wife Ester's command showed the way/means to make the Purim holiday, and ordered them to do it every year. They also wrote all those thing in the government's book of history.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maʔəmar: word, command"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">maʔəmar: word, command</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Raja Ahasuweros deng Mordekai pung hebat<bt>King Ahasuweros' and Mordekai's glory/amazingness/impressiveness</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="10" />
      <v n="1" />Raja Ahasuweros ju kasi jalan parenta ko suru samua orang di dia pung karaja'an ko bayar pajak yang pake hasil kabón, ko, karjá. Itu atoran ju kaná sampe di laut pung sablá.<bt>King Ahasuweros also enacted a command/law to order everyone in his kingdom to pay a tax using the produce from their fields, or, work. That regulation was also in effect to the other/far side of the sea. [EXEG: Earlier time, Heb word meant 1) forced labour, but later meant 2) tribute. Scholars undecided about what it meant when Esther was written. KM reading allows for both interpretations of ‘regions of the sea’ (See discusssion in TN).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maS: statute-labor. The institution of tribute"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">maS: statute-labor. The institution of tribute or corvee involves involuntary, unpaid labour or other service for a superior power-a feudal lord, a king, or a foreign ruler (Ex 1:11; Est 10:1; Lam 1:1). By Estherʔs time it may have meant forced tribute.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔiyyey: the coasts of, the regions"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔiyyey: the coasts of, the regions of; offshore islands (UBS). Pidgin speakers understand "far islands" quite well. Thatʔs where we live.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Samua yang raja bekin, samua yang kasi tunju dia pung kuasa, samua yang jadi, so'al itu orang Yahudi dong pung parkara yang bekin raja Ahasuweros angka sang Mordekai jadi orang bésar tu, pagawe di istana dong su tulis samua-samua dalam Buku Sajara Raja Orang Media deng Orang Persia dong.<bt>Everything that the king did, everything that showed his power/authority, everything that happened, about/concerning the Yahudi people's matter/issue/dispute which made Mordekai become an important person, the officials in the palace wrote everything in the History Book of the Kings of the Media and Persia People.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taqpow: his strength"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">taqpow: his strength</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gəvuwratow: his force, strength"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">gəvuwratow: his force, strength</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parashat: exact statement"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">parashat: exact statement</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gədullat: greatness"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">gədullat: greatness</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Sefer divrey hayyamiym ləmalkhey maday uwparaW:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">Sefer divrey hayyamiym ləmalkhey maday uwparaW: Book of the Annals of the Time of the Kings of Media and Persia.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Te itu orang Yahudi, andia Mordekai, nae jadi raja Ahasuweros pung tangan kanan. Mordekai ju jadi orang bésar di orang Yahudi dong pung teng-tenga. Dong ju hormat sang dia, tagal dia cari yang bae kasi dia pung orang dong sandiri. Kalo ada parkara ko, kasampatan ko, Mordekai cari jalan ko biar samua jadi bae kasi dia pung orang Yahudi dong.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) that Yahudi person, that is Mordekai, rose to become king Ahasuweros' right hand (=second in command or trusted person). Mordekai also was/became a big/important person among the Yahudi people. They honoured/respected him, because he sought the good/best for his own people. If there was an issue/dispute, or opportunity, Mordekai sought for a way to that all could become good/benefit his Yahudi people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishneh: doubling, repetition; second in command"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">mishneh: doubling, repetition; second in command</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ratsuwy (rtsh partcpl pass): one with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ratsuwy (rtsh partcpl pass): one with whom his brothers were abundantly pleased</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ʔechayw: his brothers"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">ʔechayw: his brothers</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="doresh: seeking"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">doresh: seeking</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shalowm: welfare, well-being"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">shalowm: welfare, well-being</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zarʕow: his offspring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-18 15:46:26Z" status="Information">zarʕow: his offspring</Message></Annotation></p>
  </book>
</bible>